 <P>FROM:  GREENPEACE CREW OCCUPYING THE SHELL BRENT SPAR OIL PLATFORM
DATE:  18 MAY, 1995 - DAY 19

<P>


     
     <head><H4>BELGIUM AND ICELAND JOIN PROTEST AGAINST UK GOVERNMENT</H4></head><body>

<P>We have just heard that Belgium and Iceland have joined Denmark
in the protest against the UK government's decision to allow
Shell to dump the disused Brent Spar oil platform into the North
Sea - as you can imagine, morale is very high on the Spar today
although conditions remain bearable!  The European Parliament has
also spoken out against the UK government's decision and is going
to send letters to the North Sea Conference member states -the
UK, France, Belgium, Netherlands, Denmark, Germany, Norway,
Sweden and Switzerland - to express its concern over this
deliberate pollution of the marine environment. International
pressure increases on the UK, known better as 'the dirty old man
of Europe'

<P>More good news today - Shell failed in an attempt to evict us
from the platform.  Apparently, the judge at the Edinburgh Court
of session said he wanted more time to consider his decision! 
This is a very important decision since our occupation of the
Brent Spar is the only thing stopping Shell from dumping this
toxic dilapidated oil rig into the North Sea.  Of course, Shell
were confident of the outcome and have already booked some
expensive contractors to decommission the toxic-laden platform
this weekend...all this waiting is costing them money but we are
staying as long as we have to to reverse this ridiculous plan to
dump the rig at sea!

<P>Bye from the high spirited occupants of the gently swaying
platform in the North Sea.

