 <HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>No Excuses - KOH-I-NOOR</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<IMG HEIGHT=26 WIDTH=100% SRC="excuseh.gif" ALT="Greenpeace - No Excuses">
  <HR ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=30%>

<H3>2.1.1
  Domestic Refrigeration Case Study: KOH-I-NOOR, Argentina</H3>
<P> 
  <IMG HSPACE=5 SRC="pixel.gif">
  Early in 1994, Greenpeace contacted  KOH-I-NOOR, an Argentinean domestic 
  refrigerator manufacturer (licensed by Liebherr),  about converting to  
  hydrocarbons from CFCs.   The World Bank was at the time encouraging 
  KOH-I-NOOR to use  HFC-134a and HCFC-141b for CFC replacements. The 
  conversion of the factory from CFCs, regardless of which alternative was 
  chosen,  required partial funding from the Multilateral Fund of the 
  Montreal Protocol, which is mainly administered by the World Bank. 
    </P>
<P> 
  <IMG HSPACE=5 SRC="pixel.gif">
  Paradoxically,   at a seminar hosted by the World Bank  a consensus 
  emerged between a number of manufacturers that cyclopentane was indeed a 
  viable alternative to CFC-11 and HCFC-141b as a blowing agent in 
  insulation foam production.  
    </P>
<P> 
  <IMG HSPACE=5 SRC="pixel.gif">
  Citing safety reasons,  the experts from the  World Bank/Multilateral 
  Fund, at first discouraged the use hydrocarbons .  However,  since most 
  Argentinean stoves and many taxis run on natural gas, many of which pose 
  potentially greater safety problems, dealing with gas-safety was not 
  considered problematic by the manufacturers. 
    </P>
<P> 
  <IMG HSPACE=5 SRC="pixel.gif">
  There was also pressure from the Argentinean Government for an early 
  completion of project submissions to the Multilateral Fund. This put 
  hydrocarbon technology at a disadvantage by limiting the available time 
  for disseminating information to the manufacturers about this innovation 
  in refrigeration. 
    </P>
<P> 
  <IMG HSPACE=5 SRC="pixel.gif">
  However,  in cooperation with Liebherr,   KOH-I-NOOR  established the 
  fact that the safety of hydrocarbon refrigerants was not a problem,  
  that hydrocarbons performed satisfactorily with existing equipment, and  
  that developing a line of refrigerators using isobutane would be 
  feasible. 
    </P>
<P> 
  <IMG HSPACE=5 SRC="pixel.gif">
  Concurrently,  as a result of Greenpeace's Greenfreeze campaign,  a high 
  degree of public support for'Greenfreeze' technology was generated in 
  Argentina.  This public response further convinced KOH-I-NOOR  of the 
  unique market opportunity presented by  the hydrocarbon option. 
    </P>
<P> 
  <IMG HSPACE=5 SRC="pixel.gif">
  KOH-I-NOOR completed its project preparation in April 1995. The project 
  relies completely on hydrocarbon technology,-- cyclopentane for foam 
  blowing, and isobutane for the refrigerant.
  The project was submitted for approval to the Multilateral Fund, and in 
  July, 1995 it was finally approved.  The production of ozone and climate 
  friendly refrigerators in Argentina will begin  as soon as funds are 
  available from the Multilateral Fund. 
    </P>
<P> 
  <IMG HSPACE=5 SRC="pixel.gif">
  The KOH-I-NOOR project is further demonstration of the fact that 
  hydrocarbons represent cost- effective and efficient alternatives to 
  CFCs.
</P>
  <HR WIDTH=80%>
 <P ALIGN=CENTER>
 <A HREF="5excuse.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="gpdotbk.gif" ALT="Go Back"></A>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="gpdotup.gif" ALT="Index: No Excuses"></A> 
