<HEAD>
<TITLE>Special Report: Climate Change and River Flooding</TITLE>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<IMG SRC="floodhead.gif" ALT="GREENPEACE: Climate Change and River Flooding">
</P>
<HR WIDTH=80%>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Preface</H1>








Greenpeace International commissioned this short study in November 1994 into 
the relationship between climate change and flooding, because of a growing belief 
that the first signs of human induced climate change are becoming evident in 
the global record of temperature, precipitation and related extreme events. The 
results of this study confirm our concerns.
<P>
Summarized in laymen's terms, this study has found:<P>
<IMG SRC="gpdotsm.gif">	River flooding is likely to increase with climate change due to the 
enhanced greenhouse effect, owing to a general increase in precipitation 
and to changes in the intensity and duration of extreme rainfall events.
<P>
<IMG SRC="gpdotsm.gif">	Global Climate Models (GCMs) all project increases in global 
precipitation as CO2 and other greenhouse gases increase in the 
atmosphere. These models also indicate that the frequency of high 
rainfall events will increase, whenever this aspect of their GCM projections have been studied.
<P>
<IMG SRC="gpdotsm.gif">	Observations of precipitation records for the World, Canada, USA and 
Europe, show an increase. The geographical pattern of observed 
precipitation trends is broadly consistent with the projections of climate 
models. Streamflow observations in the USA and Europe also show an 
increase in recent decades that is consistent with GCM projections.
<P>
<IMG SRC="gpdotsm.gif">	Particular findings for the USA and Europe include:<P>
		<DD><IMG SRC="gpdotsmsm.gif">	Increasing streamflow trends from 559 gauges in the USA from 
1941-1988 are consistent with the enhanced greenhouse forcing 
hypothesis. Precipitation in Canada and the USA has increased by 
7.6% from 1891-1990. One study, from 14 stations, indicates that the 
daily maximum precipitation intensity increased significantly from 
1916-1985.
		<DD><IMG SRC="gpdotsmsm.gif">	Increasing streamflow trends are evident in North Europe. In Germany 
14 stations indicate that runoff increased significantly over the period 
1931-1988, with runoff values after 1964 being 26% higher than in the 
preceding period. Precipitation increased significantly over this period 
i.e. in Bavaria, 40% between 1960 and 1990. In the Meuse river the 
peak runoff near Maastricht has increased 10-12% since 1911 and the 
wintertime precipitation has increased this century (1911-1993) by 
20% compared to the 1882-1910 period.

<P>

<IMG SRC="gpdotsm.gif">	The circumstances immediately prior and during the recent floods 
(1993,1995) in Europe are consistent with the projections of the climate 
models and are indicative of the kinds of events that are likely to 
become more common as the global climate warms. The consistency is in 
several directions, particularly changes to the wintertime weather sys-
tems and increases in amount, intensity and duration of precipitation. 
These record floods, however, are not unique, having occurred once 
before this century, and cannot be directly attributed to the enhanced 
greenhouse effect.
<P>
These latter events highlight the risks associated with increasing concentrations 
of CO2 and other greenhouse gases. Greenpeace is not alone in this belief. 
Munich Re, the world's largest reinsurance company, said of the January 1995 
European floods that they "point to a possible global warming". 
<P>
Greenpeace hopes that the results of this study will contribute to two major 
international processes in 1995:
<P>
<IMG SRC="gpdotsm.gif">	The First Conference of the Parties to the United Nations Framework 
Convention on Climate Change to be held in Berlin, 28 March to 7 April 
is required to review the adequacy of the existing commitments for 
industrialized countries to stabilize their emissions at 1990 levels by the 
year 2000. With the 1994 Report of the IPCC on Radiative Forcing Of 
Climate Change concluding in its work on carbon cycle modelling that 
"perhaps the most important result .... is that stabilization of [global] 
emissions does not lead to stabilization of CO2 concentration", it is clear 
that further emission reductions are essential.
<P>
<IMG SRC="gpdotsm.gif">	The IPCC is concluding its Second Assessment Report on Climate Change 
in December 1995 and in the course of this is preparing a report in 
Article 2 of the Climate Convention. This Article states that the 
convention's ultimate objective is to achieve stabilization of greenhouse 
gas concentrations in the atmosphere at a level that would prevent 
dangerous anthropogenic interference with the climate system" with this 
being "achieved within a time frame sufficient to allow ecosystems to 
adapt naturally to climate change, to ensure that food production is not 
threatened and to enable economic development to proceed in a 
sustainable manner". 
<P>
By demonstrating some of the potential consequences of climate change this 
study provides a powerful incentive for further legally binding commitments to 
reduce CO2 and other greenhouse gas emissions, which can, over time, stabilize 
greenhouse concentrations at safe levels.
<P>

<B><I>W.L. Hare</I></B><BR>
Climate Policy Director<BR>
Greenpeace International<BR>
<HR>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="gpdotbk.gif" ALT="Go Back"></A>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="gpdotup.gif" ALT="Go Home"></A> 
<A HREF="floodack.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="gpdotfd.gif" ALT="Go Forward"></A> 
</P>
