</DOCHDR>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Special Report: Climate Change and River Flooding</TITLE>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<IMG SRC="floodhead.gif" ALT="GREENPEACE: Climate Change and River Flooding">
</P>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<HR WIDTH=80%>

<H2>2.2.	Circulation patterns</H2>

Changes in atmospheric circulation patterns are also considered as an indicator 
of a possible climate change. Obviously, a close relationship exists between type 
of atmospheric circulation and the prevalence of rainfall. There is observational 
evidence that the frequency of certain European circulation patterns has 
changed over during the last 30 years (i.e. Zwart, 1992; 1993). GCMs indicate 
changes in the Northern Hemisphere Storm tracks (Hall et al., 1994). We will 
explore this further in the later chapters.
<P>
<HR>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<A HREF="2-1.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="gpdotbk.gif" ALT="Go Back"></A>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="gpdotup.gif" ALT="Go Home"></A> 
<A HREF="3-0.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="gpdotfd.gif" ALT="Go Forward"></A> 
</P>
