<HEAD>
<TITLE>Special Report: Climate Change and River Flooding</TITLE>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<IMG SRC="floodhead.gif" ALT="GREENPEACE: Climate Change and River Flooding">
</P>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<HR WIDTH=80%>

<H2>3.1.	Characteristics of GCMs</H2>

General circulation models are extensions of existing weather forecasting models, 
obviously operating on different time and spatial scales. The modelling with 
regards to rainfall is based on fairly straightforward physical theory. It would 
therefore be surprising if the model predictions were very different from what 
theoretically can be expected. The power of these models lies in the fact that 
they account for the overall effect of several complicated processes, and that 
they have the potential to give quantitative estimates. 
<P>
The GCMs can be used to simulate both the present climate and the 
greenhouse-effect induced changes of the climate. They operate on the 
three-dimensional scale. Large-scale processes are resolved explicitly. Processes on 
scales that cannot be resolved ("subgrid scales") are incorporated by 
parametrisation. Statistical properties, derived from both observational and 
theoretical studies, are then related to the resolved-scale variables (temperature, 
humidity, wind and pressure). 
<P>
<A NAME="r1">In earlier research</A>, GCM studies were carried out with the ocean represented as a 
mixed layer<A HREF="3-1.html#f1">*</A>. Fairly recently, finance, processing speed and computational skill 
have allowed atmospheric models to be coupled to oceanic general circulation 
models. In these coupled ocean-atmosphere GCMs, the changes in climate are 
assessed by "transient response" experiments: simulations usually carried out 
with a 1% increase per year in equivalent CO2 concentrations, consistent with 
the "business-as-usual" scenarios described by the IPCC (1990). The results are 
compared with those of a control run in which the equivalent CO2 
concentrations are held constant<A HREF="3-1.html#f2">**</A>.
<P>
Rainfall is usually estimated by two schemes in the GCM: a convection scheme 
and a large-scale condensation scheme. As in nature, both processes can be active 
at the same time (e.g., Hewitson and Crane, 1992). The result is a vertical 
transport of heat, moisture and momentum from the atmospheric boundary 
layer to higher levels, which may eventually lead to precipitation. Condensation 
takes place when the water vapour content exceeds the saturation value. After 
correcting for the release of latent heat and sub-grid effects, the remainder 
precipitates as water or snow.
<P>
Typical GCM models have a horizontal resolution of 300 to 1000 km2. This is 
sufficient to represent the large-scale features of the climate, but allow only a 
limited interpretation on regional scales. Alternative schemes for regional 
estimations have therefore been developed: a nested approach in which 
high-resolution regional climate models are driven by large-scale GCM output, 
and statistical methods which correlate the regional climate to the large-scale 
flow. The results from GCMs become less reliable on smaller geographical and 
time scales. On the regional scales, projections suffer from significant errors, and 
tend to differ from model to model (IPCC, 1992). 
<P>
Climate perturbation is usually expressed in terms of the change of mean values. 
However, it has been recognised that the occurrence of extreme events may have 
a greater impact than changes in the mean climate itself (Katz and Brown, 1991), 
but modelling of extreme events is difficult due to the scale incompatibility. 
Most deductions on the small-scale events are made indirectly, i.e. by 
considering changes in the mean and/or in the variability. 

<HR>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<A HREF="3-0.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="gpdotbk.gif" ALT="Go Back"></A>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="gpdotup.gif" ALT="Go Home"></A> 
<A HREF="3-2.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="gpdotfd.gif" ALT="Go Forward"></A> 
</P>
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=-1>
<B>Footnotes:</B><BR>
<A NAME="f1">*</A> In the uppermost layer of the ocean the temperature is relatively uniform in depth. 
The disadvantage of the mixed-layer models is that any variability associated with 
oceanic transport, e.g. the El Nio Southern Oscillation (ENSO), cannot be simulated. 
<A HREF="3-1.html#r1">Return</A>
<P>
<A NAME="f2">**</A>	In the cross-comparison of the GCM projections in the next section, reference is 
made to CO2 equivalent values. <A HREF="3-1.html#r1">Return</A>
</FONT SIZE>
</BODY>
