<IMG ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=5 SRC="solrevdef.gif"><BR>


<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>New Energy Deal</H1>





<I>
"Behold the blessed vision of the sun no longer pouring his energies 
unregulated into space but by means of photo  electric cells and thermopiles 
these powers gathered into electric store houses to the total extinction of 
steam engines and the utter repression of smoke".</I><FONT SIZE=-1> Rolo Appleyard - solar researcher - 1891</FONT SIZE>
  
  
  <P>
Energy is a basic resource without which much of what we expect from 
industrial societies would be impossible. For developing countries access to 
secure energy supplies and to efficient energy using technologies is one of 
the pre-requisites for economic and social development.
   <P> 
Ecologically however the world cannot afford a continuation  of  
industrialized countries' energy intensive consumption  pattern, nor for 
developing countries to follow that path  into the future.
   <P> 

The scale of the problem can be seen from a few simple numbers. Mid-range 
estimates project a five-fold increase in global primary energy demand by 
2100 along with a 3.5 fold increase in CO2 emissions from 6.1 billion tonnes 
of carbon per year to around 21 billion tonnes. Apart from a multitude of 
other serious environmental problems associated with the use of fossil fuels, 
such as  acid rain, such an increase in CO2 emissions would lead to massive 
climatic change. 
    <P>
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="sundotsm.gif" ALT="dot!"> <B><I>Fossil fuel failure</B></I>
    <P>
       
Huge infusions of lending for energy infrastructure averaging $40 billion 
every year over the past 20 years have resulted in  crushing debt loads for 
many developing countries. Newly- industrialising nations are discovering  
that  fossil fuel  energy sources come at a high  economic, social and 
environmental cost.
  <P>
The 'nuclear option' has also proved an expensive failure in the  
industrialised world,  where a virtual standstill in nuclear  projects has been 
in  force for some years. Worse, these  nuclear programmes have resulted in 
large stockpiles of weapons- usable plutonium. 
  <P>
The need to meet the world's energy needs at a time of ecological limits on 
energy use and increasingly scarce  capital for energy expansion, demands 
new solutions which step off the road of unsustainable and destabilising 
fossil and nuclear fuels.  
  <P>
The new solutions can achieve the benefits of affordable and  sustainable 
energy without the  drawbacks of conventional  fuels for all nations, 
including  the world's poorest.  The time has come for a new, global energy 
deal.
  <P>
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="sundotsm.gif" ALT="dot!"> <B><I>Fossil free future</I></B>
  <P>
  <IMG ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=8 SRC="srdonkey.gif">
A global economic and energy modelling study commissioned by Greenpeace 
from the Stockholm Environment Institute investigated the feasibility of 
avoiding dangerous rates of  climate change.
  <P>
 
The main results of the study, which adopted conventional UN economic 
development and population growth assumptions, demonstrate that it is  
economically and technically feasible to phase out fossil fuels and nuclear 
power. Major improvements in energy efficiency, especially in the  transport, 
buildings and electricity sectors would yield major  reductions in CO2 
emissions. The rapid introduction of renewables such as wind, solar and 
biomass is essential to  both achieve the early reductions in emissions and to 
ultimately eliminate CO2 emissions.  
  <P>
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="sundotsm.gif" ALT="dot!"> <B><I>The solutions</I></B>
  <P>  
Energy efficiency combined with advanced renewable power systems can 
address both the environmental and economic costs of supplying energy 
services.  
    <P>
Energy services are what people, or industry actually use. These include 
cooking, lighting, industrial process heat, transport, and so on. Energy supply 
(i.e. coal, oil, gas, nuclear, solar, biofuels, hydro) is the raw material used to 
drive the energy service.  Energy efficiency refers to the quantity (and 
quality) of the energy supply used to create a unit of   energy service. The 
higher the efficiency the lower is the required amount of energy supply. 
   <P> 
There is vast scope for improving the efficiency of energy  use both now 
with available technology and in the future  with continuing technological  
development.
    <P>
     <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=8 SRC="sreli.gif">
Renewable energy is energy that can be obtained, directly or indirectly, from 
natural flows of sunlight, water, and air. Renewable systems include solar 
photovoltaic power systems, solar hot water systems, wind turbines, bio-fuel 
plantations, hydroelectric systems and so on.  These energy sources are 
sustainable because they never 'run out'.  Most   importantly, though, is the 
fact that many renewable energy   applications such as wind power and 
solar thermal are already cheaper than conventional fuels, even though fossil 
and nuclear power enjoy the advantage that their price does not reflect their 
full environmental and economic costs.
    <P>
Many of these energy options can be designed, built, and exploited locally 
and at less economic cost than conventional systems. They produce strong 
positive impacts for national economies because they exploit indigenous 
labour and materials. In rural areas, the most sophisticated solar arrays can 
provide sufficient high-quality energy at a cost lower than from electricity 
grids - and radically improve the living conditions of the world's poorest 
people. 
    <P>
Similar solar solutions are also available for industrial applications to supply 
reliable grid connected electricity. In the United States, as part of a plan to 
develop a 1,000 MW Solar Enterprise Zone in the Nevada desert, ENRON has 
announced plans to build a 100 MW solar power station. Such a power 
station would be the largest solar operation in the United States, producing 
enough power for a city of 100,000 people.  
    <P>
Most important of all is the need to spark a rapid growth in the use of 
renewable energy technologies.  Developed countries must take the lead in 
sharing the existing  technology - both advanced and mundane - that  makes 
the  solar revolution possible. These countries should aim to achieve a 
minimum 3% per year penetration of their own energy supply system with 
renewable technologies. Developing countries need to adopt policies which 
favour renewable energy over yet more huge centralised power stations.
    <P>
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="sundotsm.gif" ALT="dot!"> <B><I>Solar power for the developing world</B></I>
    <P>
On the eve of the 21st century 2 billion people, some seventy per cent of the 
developing world's population, are without electricity, reliant on 19th 
century fuels to provide basic services, such as lighting. Solar photovoltaics 
(PV) offers developing nations an immediate and direct alternative to 
kerosene lamps, diesel generators, fossil fuelled utilities and expensive grid 
extensions, while satisfying the demand for household electric power.  
    <P>
Today some 200,000 families around the world use small household PV 
systems to power energy efficient lighting and other appliances. These 
people represent the largest group of domestic users of solar electricity in 
the world.  For the vast majority of the two billion people without electricity, 
solar PV is the most cost effective, affordable and available power source.
    <P>
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="sundotsm.gif" ALT="dot!"> <B><I>Solar potential</I></B>
    <P>
Currently the size of the PV world market (some 60 MW/year)  is well below 
what is required to satisfy the demands of the rural population of the 
developing world. The total capacity of PV that would be required to meet 
the basic needs of the 2 billion people without electricity services is some 
140 GW of PV.  Since 1976 some 450 MW of solar PV  has been produced.
    <P>
The European Commission's Power for the World' programme (a global PV 
action plan) estimates providing solar electricity to a billion people in the 
developing world would cost $60 billion ($3 billion a year for 20 years). This 
is only 3% of annual energy investments in developing countries and less 
than 0.5% of current military expenditure.
    <P>
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="sundotsm.gif" ALT="dot!"> <B><I>Solar case studies</I></B>                   
    <P>
200,000 solar PV systems are installed around the world, including 37,000 
in Mexico, 20,000 in Kenya, 16,000 in Indonesia, 15,000 in China, 4,500 in 
Sri Lanka, 4,000 in the Dominican Republic and 1,000 in Brazil.
    <P>
    <IMG ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=8 SRC="srpanel.gif">
In Kenya more rural households obtain their electricity from  solar energy 
than from the official policy of grid extension.  Around 1 MW of PV power 
has been installed in Kenya. Around 20,000 households have purchased solar 
PV for their homes compared to the 17,000 connected to the official rural 
electrification programme.
    <P>
     
In the Dominican Republic, Enersol, a US-based non-governmental 
organisation, has successfully trained local entrepreneurs to assemble, 
market, install and service PV systems, and to develop a community based 
solar NGO to manage revolving loan funds allowing full cost recovery finance 
of the solar systems. The programme began in 1985 with 6 systems, grew to 
a 100 in 1987, more than 1,000 in 1989 and 4,500 in 1994. Since 1992, 
Enersol has replicated their successful Dominican programme in Honduras 
and Guatemala and contributed to projects in Bolivia and Costa Rica. The 
Solar Electric Light Fund (SELF) has taken the Enersol model and has 
established a number of successful solar seed' projects around the world.  
    <P>
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="sundotsm.gif" ALT="dot!"> <B><I>Start the solar revolution</I></B>
  <P>
<I>" ...power grids are themselves no longer necessarily  desirable.........what's 
required is a global effort to   accelerate the development of cost-effective 
photovoltaic cells."</I> <BR>
<DD><FONT SIZE=-1> - Vice President Al Gore</FONT SIZE>
  <P>
<I>"The often heard claim that photovoltaics is too expensive cannot be true 
otherwise its success in the world's poorest villages would be a paradox." </I> <BR> 
<DD><FONT SIZE=-1> - Dr Wolfgang Paltz, European Commission</FONT SIZE><BR>
  <P>
   <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=8 SRC="srroof.gif">
In the developing world, solar electric power generation is cost-competitive 
with utility grid extensions. Despite the high up front costs, solar 
electrification remains the least   cost alternative when calculated over the 
twenty year life of the solar panels. Utilising the sun's distribution system is 
far cheaper than stringing wires at $10,000 a mile to deliver fossil fuelled or 
nuclear powered electricity to rural populations.
  <P>
With a wholesale re-direction of the lending regimes of multilateral banks, 
such as the World Bank so that priority is given to energy efficiency and 
renewable energy solar power will allow governments to deliver their 
promises of electricity for all without jeopardising the environment.
  <P>
  
<HR WIDTH=70%>
<P>
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="sundotsm.gif" ALT="dot!"> <I><B>Postscript: What is photovoltaic (PV) technology ?</B></I>
<P>
PV power is the conversion of sunlight 
directly into   electricity. The photo (light) voltaic (effect) was first 
discovered in the 18th century.  The first solar cells were developed in 1954. 
Since 1980 costs have dropped ten fold making PV a cost-effective way of 
delivering pollution free electricity directly to the user. As well as providing 
reliable cost- effective pollution free electricity solar PV provides additional 
benefits such as improved health, literacy and education and helps to slow 
urban migration. 
<P>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<A HREF="solrev1.html"><IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=middle SRC="solrevbk.gif" ALT="Back"></A>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=middle SRC="srhome.gif" ALT="Home"></A>
