<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Funding Climate Change?</H1>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>The World Bank's fossil fuel addiction</H3>


Developing country economies are directly threatened by climate change, as 
forestries, fisheries, agriculture, and human health face major challenges. 
Almost all of the developing country signatories to the climate convention 
are members of the World Bank and other regional multilateral development 
banks (MDBs).
  <P>
The climate convention will allocate funds to help developing countries set 
up projects aimed at reducing CO2 emissions, largely through the Global 
Environment Facility (GEF) administered by the World Bank.  Under the 
Climate Convention, the GEF's main aim is to help developing countries in the 
fight against climate change through renewable energy projects
   <P> 
Since negotiations for the climate convention began in 1991, developing 
countries continue to oppose the World Bank's management of the GEF, and 
with good reason.  
    <P>
Most of the World Bank's involvement with climate change has  been in 
funding it. The bank has financed enormous fossil fuel projects in developing 
countries through its energy lending- departments where the policies totally 
ignore the Bank's responsibilities under the comparatively tiny GEF. In 1994, 
the Bank lent $2.76 billion in the conventional energy sector and $3.29 
billion in the transport sector. Compare this with GEF projects which will add 
up to just $300 million a year. A losing battle in the fight against climate 
change. 
    <P>
The regional development banks, especially the Asian Development Bank, 
are taking the lead in starting to work towards developing renewable energy 
policies for all their energy lending. But the World Bank continues to operate 
with inconsistent energy policies - one arm funding huge fossil fuel projects 
and the other feebly trying to stop it. 
    <P>
Furthermore, more than half of the GEF's designated Global Warming' 
projects in pilot phase went to energy projects in the fossil fuel sector. 
    <P>
The result. Local pollution levels soar and global CO2 emissions continue to 
increase dramatically.
    <P>
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="sundotsm.gif" ALT="dot!"> <B>Greenpeace demands:</B>
<P>
In order to meet their commitments under the GEF, the Multilateral 
Development Banks must adopt a consistent CO2 reduction policy across all 
energy lending, to be based on comprehensive least cost energy plans, and 
including environmental and social costs in sector and project
 evaluations.
  <P>
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="sundotsm.gif" ALT="dot!"> <B>A Case In Point: India</B><BR>
<P>
  <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=8 SRC="srshack.gif">
In 1994, the World Bank announced a new commitment to enhance 
renewable energy development.  But its double standards persisted. While 
the bank's intentions seemed honourable, it continues to support, with a 
$400 million loan, a controversial 2000 MW coal fired power plant expansion 
in the Singrauli region in eastern central India.  No Environmental Impact 
Assessment was carried out, no least cost energy plan was laid out, and 
certainly no CO2 emissions have been calculated.  
  <P>

Over the next ten years, the World Bank plans to provide $1.2 billion for the 
construction of 14 new coal fired power plants and two gas-fired power 
plants around India. This expansion plan will produce an annual minimum 
100 million tonnes of CO2.   On top of this, a  $300 million coal mining 
expansion loan is currently under preparation for India.
  <P>
At Singrauli, the World Bank's project has led to the relocation of 51,000 
people; coal mining has turned the area into a moonlike landscape; drinking 
water is polluted and there are widespread health problems.  Ironically, 
about 60% of the regions' inhabitants do not have electricity in their homes - 
it is mostly exported. 
  <P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<A HREF="solrev2.html"><IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=middle SRC="solrevbk.gif" ALT="Back"></A>
