<IMG ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=5 SRC="solrevdef.gif"><BR>


<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Questions And Answers On The Climate Protocol</H1>

<BR CLEAR>
.
  <P>
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="sundotsm.gif" ALT="dot!"> <B>Q: Why does the Climate Convention need a Protocol?</B>
  <P>
 <B>A:</B>   The Framework Convention on Climate Change is just that - a framework.  
Real progress towards the achievement of its objective can only come 
through the adoption of a protocol (or protocols) to the Convention. Protocols 
are crucial: without them, the Convention would become an ineffective and 
useless 'sleeping treaty.' For example, the emission commitments in the 
convention only require that developed countries stabilize their emissions at 
1990 levels from the year 2000, yet real reductions are needed to avert the 
threat of massive climate change.
    <P>
When the convention was negotiated it was agreed that the Berlin Climate 
Summit would  review the adequacy of  the emission commitments for 
developed countries and  take appropriate action   
  <P>
The consensus of legal views is that negotiation of the protocol is preferable 
to amending the Convention itself, owing to its complexity.
    <P>
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="sundotsm.gif" ALT="dot!"> <B>Q:  How does it work? </B>
    <P>
<B>A:</B>   Adoption of a protocol by the Convention does not become  legally 
binding until the required number of countries have ratified it, and then 
only on those countries that have done so. The voting requirements for 
adoption of a protocol have  yet to be agreed, and in fact remain hotly 
disputed.
    <P>
A protocol needs to be proposed six months before the Conference of the 
Parties for it to be considered for adoption.
    <P>
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="sundotsm.gif" ALT="dot!"> <B>Q:  Are there any examples in place now? </B>
    <P>
<B>A:</B>   The 1987 Montreal Protocol on Substances that Deplete  the Ozone Layer, 
has delivered a concrete programme for progressively eliminating the 
production and consumption of ozone-depleting substances such as CFCs.  
The 1985 Vienna Convention on the Protection of the Ozone Layer provided 
the legal framework  for the Montreal Protocol.   Since its inception, and as 
the ozone layer deteriorated, the Montreal  Protocol has been tightened up, 
making major advances  towards stopping production of the harmful gases 
which destroy the ozone layer.  
    <P>
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="sundotsm.gif" ALT="dot!"> <B>Q:  Are there any proposals on the table for Berlin?</B>
    <P>
<B>A:</B>   The Permanent Representative of Trinidad and Tobago to  the United 
Nations in New York, on behalf of the 36 nation  Alliance of Small Island 
States, submitted a draft protocol  on 20 September, 1994, calling for 
developed countries to  adopt a CO2 emission reduction target of 20% from 
1990 levels by the year 2005.  The German Government submitted  further 
elements  to the AOSIS protocol on 22 September.   Both documents have 
now been formally transmitted by official negotiators to Berlin.
    <P>
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="sundotsm.gif" ALT="dot!"> <B>Q:  Whose responsibility is it to negotiate the Protocol?</B>
    <P>
<B>A:</B>   All Parties to the Convention have to be involved in its  negotiation.  The 
main responsibility however lies with the biggest CO2 polluters of the 
industrialised countries - the OECD, central and eastern Europe and the 
Russian Federation.
    <P>
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="sundotsm.gif" ALT="dot!"> <B>Q: What is the main element it should contain?</B>
    <P>
<B>A:</B>   A Protocol should include, at a minimum, the commitment  for 
industrialised countries to cut CO2 emissions by 20% by  2005 i.e. a target 
and a timetable for emission reductions.   This would, however, be just a first 
step towards cutting  CO2 emissions back to a safe level.  
    <P>
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="sundotsm.gif" ALT="dot!"><B>Q:  Can a protocol still be adopted at Berlin?</B>
    <P>
<B>A:</B>   Yes, given sufficient political will from developed countries. 
    <P>
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="sundotsm.gif" ALT="dot!"> <B>Q: What else should a protocol contain?</B>
    <P>
<B>A:</B>   In order to support country programmes to meet emission  reduction 
targets, and to overcome competitiveness concerns, the protocol also needs to 
contain  a package of measures  stating clear objectives for:
  <UL>
   <DT><IMG ALIGN=top SRC="sundotsm.gif" ALT="dot!"> Global minimal standards for  international  energy- consuming 
technologies, such as motor vehicles
  <P>
   <DT><IMG ALIGN=top SRC="sundotsm.gif" ALT="dot!"> Standards for increased adoption of energy efficiency  and renewable 
energy technologies,
  <P>
   <DT><IMG ALIGN=top SRC="sundotsm.gif" ALT="dot!"> Adoption of climate friendly policies in the field of  buildings and 
transport, as well as for the management of electricity and gas utilities i.e. 
integrated resource planning (IRP).  
  <P>
   <DT><IMG ALIGN=top SRC="sundotsm.gif" ALT="dot!"> Removal of subsidies to fossil fuels and nuclear power. The protocol also 
needs to contain commitments to provide  financial and technology 
assistance for developing countries in order  to accelerate the adoption of the 
energy efficiency and renewable energy systems.
  </UL>
  <P>
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="sundotsm.gif" ALT="dot!"> <B>Q:  Why not just measures and polices rather than targets and  timetables 
for emission reductions?</B>
  <P>
 <B>A:</B>   Without clear emission targets to drive the development  of policies and 
measures, the latter will be little more  than statements of the lowest 
common denominator. Negotiations on targets and timetables are necessary 
to send  a clear signal to policy makers and industry.  In this context, legally 
binding  targets and timetables  for emission reductions have been essential, 
for example, to the  success of the Montreal Protocol.  Indeed, without the 
existence of the current target in the Convention, it is  doubtful whether the 
current public policy debates occurring  in many industrialised countries 
now would be as sharp and focused as they are.  As industrialized
 countries grapple in the next  phase of their national plans to limit CO2 and 
other greenhouse gas emissions, the existence of targets will become more 
and more important as a basic, underlying policy  parameter.  
  <P>
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="sundotsm.gif" ALT="dot!"> <B>Q:  What are some of the obstacles to the adoption of a protocol?</B>
<P>
<OL>
<LI> The failure of many industrialised countries to demonstrate  that they can 
and will implement their existing commitments  in the Convention has 
caused many developing countries, including China, to question the motives 
behind a protocol  negotiation at this stage.
  <P>
<LI> The USA, Canada, Australia and New Zealand have linked  further 
emission commitments by industrialized countries to  commitments by 
developing countries.  This is seen by developing countries as grossly unfair 
and against the principles in the convention.  Whilst most participants 
acknowledge the need for developing countries to ultimately  take action, it 
is widely accepted that the first phase in  the global response has to be taken 
by developed countries,  which produce over 75% of global CO2 emissions.
  <P>
<LI> The negotiators are still stuck in a discussion on the  voting rules for the 
adoption of a protocol (Rule 42).   It  is up to the Convention process to 
decide its own rules and  these need to be adopted at Berlin.   However some 
Parties,  particularly the OPEC states Saudi Arabia and Kuwait, want a  
Protocol to be adopted by consensus.  This would effectively  block any 
protocol with emission commitments.   The two thirds majority also proposed 
is enough to reflect the will of the meeting.  
</OL>  

<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<A HREF="solrev4.html"><IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=middle SRC="solrevbk.gif" ALT="Back"></A>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=middle SRC="srhome.gif" ALT="Home"></A>
<A HREF="solrev6.html"><IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=middle SRC="solrevfor.gif" ALT="Forward"></A>
</P>
