<HEAD>
<TITLE>2020 - The Future if Berlin Summit Succeeds</TITLE>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="2020genhead.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Climate News"><BR>
</P>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+2>Daimler Benz successful</FONT SIZE><BR>
<I>
Profits from sales above all with public
transport systems
</I>
</P>
<BR>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<HR WIDTH=80%>
<P>


The Daimler Benz company's sales rose again last year by eleven per
cent. As its chairman reported at its annual press conference in
Berlin, only 20 per cent of the total company profit - made by its
subsidiary, Mercedes Benz - still came from private cars. Production
was exclusively of fuel-efficient cars doing over 115 miles to the
gallon.      
<P>
In 2019 roughly 60 per cent of sales were accounted for by
public transport, telecommunications, and its new subsidiary, the
Daimler Benz Car-Sharing company.  Daimler Benz's leading position in
environmentally-friendly private transport worldwide had, so the
company chairman said, been apparent at the trade fair on mobility
which had just come to an end.  There had been great interest in the
new energy-saving train and the further refined call-bus systems.
Mobility consultancy to local authorities and regions had increased
strongly, accounting for 15 per cent of total sales in 2019.
<HR>
