<html>
<head>
<title>STOP THE HERRING DERBY!</title>
</head>
<body background="../icons/back5.gif" body bgcolor="345599" text="9cfcfc" LINK="FAF13B" VLINK="FF8300" ALINK="FFFFB8">

<P align=right>To return to the surface click on the icon...</I><a href="index.html#herr01"><image align=right src="../icons/oce01t.gif" width=60 height=50></a>

<blockquote>    


<a href="index.html#herr01"><image align=left src="../icons/fherr01.gif" width=100 height=70 border=0></a>



<br><font size=+2 COLOR="00ff55"><I><B>STOP THE HERRING DERBY!</B> </I></font>

<br clear=all><B>For the second time since the 1970s North Sea herring has been
brought to the brink of collapse. Mid way through 1996 emergency
measures had to be taken to halve the total catch allowed for
this year, throwing the fishing industry into turmoil. It is
debatable whether any catch should be allowed in 1997.

<p>Yet, at this crisis point, one of the very worst and least
defensible practices is about to start. This is the 'Herring
Derby': the annual congregation of shoals of herring that are
forced to run the gauntlet of powerful modern fishing vessels as
the fish pass from the North Sea to the English Channel to spawn. The
fishery is not primarily for the herring but for the roe, which are
exported to Japan for New Year's celebrations.</B>


<P><B><a href="../cbio/prdec11.html"><img width=40 height=40 ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 src="../icons/bionews.gif">PRESS RELEASE:</a>
December 11th 1996,  Greenpeace targets "Herring Derby" in English Channel
</b>


<p><!--a href="../cbio/*********"><img align=left border=0 width=35 height=35 src="
../icons/bioact.gif" HSPACE=5></A><B><a href="../cbio/******"> ACTION:</A> December 11th 1996  - ******</B-->


<font size=+2><p><I>Countdown to crisis:</I></font>

<B><p>In 1947 the spawning stock of North Sea herring was 5 million
tonnes. But, under a sustained onslaught, the stock was worn down
until, in the 1970s, it finally  crashed. Fishing was banned for six
long years. In the 1980s, so as to avoid a repeat, the management goal
was to build up the herring stock to 2.2 million tonnes. But the stock
never got higher than 1.3 million tonnes (in 1989) and then started to
fall. If minor but rapid adjustments in the catches had then been
made, all might have been well. 
<p>However European fisheries policy has repeatedly proved incapable of
delivering such adjustments. The blame for failure is widespread.
Fisheries scientists and managers were reluctant to believe the
evidence, knowing of the implications, and put off the warning.
Fishers demanded too many fish. A blind eye was turned to the huge
quantities that were being caught in the industrial fisheries for
sprat and other fish. A significant number of fishers mis-reported
their catches, saying that they were caught outside the North Sea, or
deliberately underestimated the amounts being sold, for example to the
eastern-European klondykers. 

<p>But in the end the buck stops with national Fisheries Ministers.
They failed to provide leadership and instead put off unpopular
decisions. The blame for this crisis rests principally with them.

<p>Earlier this year it became clear that the spawning stock had
fallen to just 500,000 tonnes and the politicians were faced with an
ultimatum from the fisheries scientists - 50% cuts now or a complete
ban in 1997, backed with the support of the European Fisheries
Commissioner, Emma Bonino. The Fisheries Ministers had little choice
but to agree to the cuts. However, as is usual, they did the absolute
minimum. 

<p>Few realise that the target they have now agreed - to restore the
stock to 800,000 tonnes - is not that of a healthy stock or that which
provides the maximum catch for fishers. It is what is called MBAL, the
Minimum Biologically Acceptable Level, below which the chance of stock
collapse is believed by fisheries scientists to increase dramatically.
One specific aspect of the scientific advice that they ignored was to
stop the Herring Derby in the English Channel.

<p><font size=+1>Herring Derby</font>
<p>The Herring Derby involves an important sub-stock of herring
which live in the North Sea proper, but spawn in the vicinity of
the Bay of Dieppe. The eggs are laid over gravel beds - where
they stick - at a depth of 20-50 metres. Upon hatching the young
drift northwards along the Dutch coast and most reach nursery
areas in the German Bight. The Derby involves principally Dutch-
owned vessels, including pair trawlers and supertrawlers, and
takes place in December. It gets its name from the frantic
manoeuvring of the boats to get the best line on the fish shoals
as they pass, and because it is all over in a  few weeks.

<p>The race is driven by the value of the roe. Vast amounts of money can
be made from it. But it is also completely unsupportable, as can be
readily confirmed by fishermen not engaged in the trade. It must stop.

<p><font size=+1>Ecological impact</font>
<p>Herring have a greater role in the world than that of making a
few fishers rich! It is one of a few species that occupy a
central place in the North Sea food-web. They are eaten by larger fish
including cod, whiting and mackerel.  Earlier this century, when
herring were abundant, it was an important food for bluefin tuna which
have since disappeared.  They are also important for other parts of
the North Sea food web, including numerous seabirds, seals, porpoises,
dolphins, orca and minke whales. Concern about the impact of the
herring fishery stretches beyond fisheries politics.


<p><font size=+1>What does Greenpeace want?</font>

<ul>
	<li>Specifically, we want the targeting of spawning stocks of
	herring in the North Sea to cease. <p>

	<li>Generally for North Sea herring catch levels should be limited
	so that the herring stock can grow to reach an interim target of
	2-3 million tonnes (what the fisheries ministers agreed in the
	1980s) and ultimately to a size that provides the maximum catches
	commensurate with minimum ecological impact.<p>

	<li>By-catch of juvenile herring in industrial fisheries must be
	rigorously restricted and controlled.<p>

	<li>Greenpeace wants a precautionary approach to be applied to
	fisheries. This concept is now recognised, by the European
	Commission and North Sea States, at least in principle, as the
	way forward with fisheries management. In simple terms it means
	that you take uncertainty fully into account, and avoid causing
	problems instead of attempting repairs after the event.<p>

 	<li>Greenpeace wants next March's crisis meeting between
	Environment and Fisheries Ministers in Bergen to agree an
	emergency recovery programme for North Sea fisheries, coupled
	with agreement on medium and long term reforms of fisheries
	management.<p>
</B><hr>
</ul>
</blockquote>
</body>
</html>

</DOC>
