<h3>Current Biodiversity/Fisheries/Forests Campaign Information</h3>
<p>
<font size=+3>One fish, two fish -- there's too few fish!</font>
<table width="100%" border=0>
<tr>
<td>
<img src="pix/trawler4.gif" vspace=0 hspace=15 width=285 height=174 
ALT="Photo of factory fishing trawler"></td>
<td>
<font size=+2><b>Factory Trawler</b> <i>n.</i> </font>An industrial scale fishing vessel,
150-300 feet in length, which catches fish by towing a large funnel-shaped net.  In around the
clock operation, factory trawlers catch and process fish in an on-board factory. This allows the
factory trawlers to stay at sea indefinitely, constantly fishing and wasting.</td>
</tr>
</table></center>
<p><a href="http://www.interactivism.com"><img align=right src="pix/inter2.gif" width=126 height=50 hspace=10 border=0></a>
<font size=-1>Greenpeace is calling for a ban on factory fishing trawlers by the year 2001. 
Concerned citizens can send a <b>free fax</b> in support of the ban to
the CEO's of Tyson Foods and American Seafoods (the largest owners
of these trawlers) by going to <b><a href="http://www.interactivism.com">www.interactivism.com</a></b><p></font>
<p><center>
<a name="diary"></a>
<hr>
<img align=middle src="pix/smtitle1.gif" width=400 height=39 ALT="Bering Sea Diary"><br>
Daily reports and photos from the ship, <i>M/V Greenpeace</i>, during our recent anti-factory trawler campaign.<p>
