</font>
For more information about our campaign against factory fishing trawlers, please read our new report, </b><a href="/~usa/reports/biodiversity/sinking_fast/index.html"><img src="/~usa/reports/biodiversity/sinking_fast/pix/sinkhed5.gif" width=565 height=100 ALT="Sinking Fast"></a><br>
<p>
<h3>...here's just a few frightening factory trawler facts...</h3></center>
<ul>
<li>There are approximately 55 Seattle-based factory trawlers operating in the North Pacific. 
Just these 55 vessels were responsible for taking 60% of the 4.4 billion pounds of fish taken in the
North Pacific.</li>
<li>Some of the factory trawlers use nets with an opening as large as 2 miles in circumference. 
You could fit 228 houses on half acre lots in the opening of just one of these nets.</li>
<li>Our fisheries are drying up. Currently, 82% of managed fish stocks in the U.S. are fully or
over-exploited. In 1994, Alaskan groundfish factory trawlers threw overboard, dead or dying, over 572 MILLION
pounds of fish because they were the wrong sex, size or species.</li>
</ul><center>
<b><a href="fishfact.html">...more frightening factory fishing facts....</a></b><br>
<b><a href="itq.html">Why is this happening?</a></b></center>
<p>
