<HEAD>
<TITLE>GREENPEACE ACTIVISTS STOP THE LOGGERS.
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCFECC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">

<table border=2 width=100% cellpadding=7><tr><td >

<a href="canada.html"><img align=right border=0 width=80 height=60 src="../icons/ncant.gif"><BR></a>
<H3>GREENPEACE ACTIVISTS STOP THE LOGGERS.</H3>
</td></tr></table>
<br><p><A HREF="act03.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="../icons/bioact.gif" HEIGHT=30 WIDTH=30 ALIGN=LEFT></A><B><A HREF="act03.html">FROM THE SCENE OF THE ACTION<BR>
</A></B> 


<p><A HREF="newsindx.html#barge"><IMG border=0 SRC="../icons/bionews.gif" HEIGHT=30 WIDTH=30 ALIGN=LEFT></A><B><A HREF="newsindx.html#barge">PRESS
RELEASES<BR>
</A></B> 
<BR clear=all>
<HR>
<BR>


<H2></H2>
<B>"Everytime the barge goes by loaded with logs, everyone knows and feels 
there's a grand theft taking place, that it's genocide for the Haida people and a continuation of the logging off of our islands for the government's and company's benefit -  They take with them our past and our future..."
<BR><FONT SIZE=-1>Ralph Stocker, of the Haidai First Nation</FONT>


<B>...The Haida Brave and the Haida Monarch are two of the largest self-loading self propelled log
barges in the world.  

<P>The barges can carry 12,000 cubic metres ( 400 logging trucks full ) of logs on thier 48 hour journey
from the Queen Charlotte Islands to Vancouver.   

<P>They are owned by timber giant MacMillan Bloedel, the company
responsible for logging more of Canada's temperate rainforests than any other.
 
<P>The barges run up and down Canada's west coast and occasionally into the
United States, moving the felled temperate rainforests of Canada to mills in Powell River, Nanaimo, Howe Sound, the Lower Mainland and Vancouver Island.

<P><font size=+1>Say Good bye to Haida Gwaii (Queen Charlotte Islands)</font>
 
<P>The Haida Brave and the Haida Monarch load up on the shores of  Haida Gwaii
two or three times per week.  This means that in one year the
barges will take away a staggering <font size=+1> <tt> $200,000,000 </tt></font>worth 
of felled Cedar, Hemlock
and Spruce. 
<P>Because 94 percent of all the rainforests cut in the region
are barged out to mills in the Lower Island or Vancouver Island for processing,
 logging in Haida Gwaii provides only 427 direct jobs to on-island residents. 
<P>The local community is calling for a 50% reduction of logging in the region and for
on-island processing facilities that would keep more jobs at home. None of the
four large logging companies currently clearcutting the rainforests of Haida
Gwaii operate processing operations on the islands.
</B><BR> <BR>






<BR><HR><BR>
