<HEAD>
<TITLE>Japan Lumber Journal, 20th June 1996
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCFECC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">

<table border=2 width=100% cellpadding=7><tr><td>
<a href="russia.html"><img align=right border=0 width=60 height=90 src="../icons/bioforar.gif"><BR></a>
<H2><B>Japanese lumber journal notes dramatic increase in Russian timber exports</B></H2>
</td></tr></table>

<blockquote>
 
<H3><B>Japan Lumber Journal, 20th June 1996
</B></H3>

<P><B>"Both Arrivals and Shipments of Russian Logs at High Level; 
Nearly the Half of Last Year Arrived for Only January-April 
This Year:
</B> 
<P>According to the All Japan Russian Logs Dealing Association, 
arrivals of Russian timber during April registered 503.700 
cubic meters, an increase of 7.7% over the same month of the 
previous year or more 5% over the previous month. It was a 
substantial arrival.

<P>The shipments are also in a good condition, registering 475.958 
cubic meters.It was an increase of 16,3% over one year ago or a 
5,5% increase from March.
<P>The largest volumes arrived at Fushiki and Toyama New Ports 
with 86.947 cubic meters, followed by Hokkaido 80.947, Maizuru 
60.514, Onahama 50.796 and Sakata 46.780. Also the largest 
volumes went out from Fushiki and Toyama New Ports with 85.899 
cubic meters, followed by Hokkaido 50,092 and Sakata 45,392. 
Onahama, Maizuru and Niigata also registered more than 30,000 
cubic meters.
Of the arrivals in April, logs for softwood plywood registered 
61,275 cubic meters. Though the figure was a little bit smaller 
than the previous month, the overall arrivals of Russian log 
for plywood for January-April have already exceeded 310,000 
cubic meters. They have already occupied 46 % of the annual 
arrivals of last year of 672,134 cubic meters.
It indicates that utilisation of softwood timber (Russian 
timber) for plywood material has been steadily increasing. It 
is supposed that the arrivals for this year may reach 800,000 - 
900,000 cubic meters if the present pace continues on as they 
are.
<P>When housing starts for March increased in two month (a good 
figure of 1.585 million units in the annual ratio), Russian 
timber that is mainly demanded for scantlings (batten products) 
of housing materials can expect of a recovery in its shipment 
in the future.
<P>How will the stocks of logs in the volume of 1,960,000 cubic 
meters as of the end of April change with recovery of shipment ?
It is no doubt that the arrivals will be less for the 
seasonal factor. It is watched with a great expectation when 
the market conditions will change."



</blockquote>


