<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Karelia</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCFECC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">

<table border=2 width=100% cellpadding=7><tr><td>
<a href="russia.html"><img align=right border=0 width=60 height=90 src="../icons/bioforar.gif"><BR></a>
<H2>KARELIAN FORESTS</H2>
</td></tr></table>

<center>

<a href="../pics/for30.gif">
<img  vspace=7 hspace=0  lowsrc="../thumbs/for30t.gif" src="../pics/for30s.gif" width=150 height=125 border=0></a>

<a href="../pics/for35.gif">
<img  vspace=7 hspace=0  lowsrc="../thumbs/for35t.gif" src="../pics/for35s.gif" width=175 height=125 border=0></a>

<a href="../pics/for31.gif">
<img  vspace=7 hspace=0  lowsrc="../thumbs/for31t.gif" src="../pics/for31s.gif" width=150 height=125 border=0></a>



</center>


<blockquote>

<P><B>Under the diligent watch of KGB, the forests
on the Russian border with Finland have been
off limits to logging for fifty years. Given the
almost complete loss of old-growth and
primary forests on the Scandinavian side of the
border, Russia's border forests are a priceless
heritage to the world. 
</B>
<P>Satellite images show the difference in stark
black and white: the Finnish forests appear as
white areas bereft of natural forests, while the
Russian side is dark with huge areas of highly
biologically and genetically diverse forests.
Crossing the border from the west is equally
telling, the Finnish forests being predominately
single-aged trees criss-crossed by drainage
ditches and marred by large open areas of
clearcuts. The natural old-growth forests of
Kostomuksha, Kalevala, Paanajarvi, Lapland,

and dozens of other areas with their varied
trees and landscapes come as a pleasing
change of something more than just scenery.

<P>However, logging of the area has begun and is
steadily increasing. Russian forest legislation
is being broken as foreign companies take
advantage of the economic crisis, carrying out
illegal logging to the doorsteps of the region's
nature reserves in order to feed the consumer
demands of Western Europe. Important nature
conservation possibilities are being
compromised, even with the involvement of
the Finnish Government, local authorities and
the Russian Federal Government, who should
instead be actively supporting a broad
conservation strategy in Karelia.

<P>In October 1995, Russian and European
environmental groups in a series of seminars
and joint press conferences demanded that all
remaining old-growth forests in Western
Russia be protected.  However, logging has
continued, and is already expanding into
biologically important but as yet unprotected
areas. Greenpeace is therefore calling on the
Governments of Karelia, Russia and Finland to
stop all logging of old-growth and primary
forests in Karelia and Finland, to establish
integrated conservation areas that cover the
whole of the border region, and to abandon
clearcutting in secondary forests that are
subject to logging.

<B><P>Greenpeace Russia is currently preparing a
World Heritage nomination for the Russian
side and is in dialogue with the Finnish
Government about the preparation of a joint
nomination. Proposals have been made to

include parts of northern Norway into the
conservation area as well.

<P> With it's extensive
experience in preparing World Heritage

nominations in Russia, Greenpeace will lead
efforts to prepare an extensive and complete
nomination and aims to convince the
governments to submit a nomination to
UNESCO that covers a continuous belt the
length of the border region some 1000
kilometres in length, including all the existing
and proposed conservation areas, buffer zones
and connecting corridors.
</B>

</blockquote>

<P><B><a href="russ03.html">The growing threat to Russian First group Forests</a></B>



<BR><HR><BR>
<a href="russia.html">return to Russian Forests page...</a>
