<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT04-B25-184</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA081-000564-B024-197</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://greenpeace.org:80/~usa/reports/biodiversity/roundup/roundup.html 193.67.176.1 19970103184306 text/html 28341
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Fri, 03 Jan 1997 18:45:45 GMT
Server: Apache/1.0.0
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 28169
Last-modified: Wed, 09 Oct 1996 23:18:56 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>"Greenpeace Report - Not Ready for Roundup: Why Consumers Should Avoid..."</title>
<META Name="description" Content="Greenpeace report documenting the faults of genetically engineered foods.">
<META Name="keywords" Content="genetic engineering soy beans Monsanto farming pesticides Roundup Greenpeace USA environment">
<body bgcolor="#FF FF FF" text="#00 00 00" link="#00 80 00"
vlink="#80 00 00" alink="#FF FF 00" basefont=3>
<center><img src="pix/roundup3.gif" width=504 height=100 ALT="Not Ready for Roundup"></center><p>
<p>
<table width=575 cellpadding=6 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr>
<td valign=top>
<img src="pix/rdupsign.gif" width=116 height=207 ALT="photo of Roundup sign in soybean field">
</td>
<td valign=top>
This fall, U.S. farmers will harvest the first crop of genetically engineered
soybeans. This represents a crucial step in the start of a massive genetic
experiment in which humans beings and the environment are the guinea pigs.    
<p> 
Roundup Ready Soybeans (RRS) are engineered by Monsanto to resist Roundup,
which is Monsanto's trade name for the herbicide glyphosate. RRS contains gene
sequences from a cauliflower mosaic virus (CMV), a petunia and a bacterium
(Agrobacterium sp).  While this year's crop accounts for less than 2 percent of U.S.
soybean production, Monsanto hopes that as much as 33 percent of the soybean crop will
be planted to RRS in the U.S. in 1997.  RRS is set to become the first
genetically engineered food to be distributed widely unless consumers and
farmers take action now.  As much as 60 percent of processed consumer food products
contain soybean material - from margarine to baby food and chocolate bars. 
<p> 
The U.S. produces most of the world's soybeans and exports about half its crop
to Europe and Asia. 
<p> 
Monsanto opposes separation of products containing Roundup Ready Soybeans,
which means that any of the thousands of food products containing soy material
might contain genetically engineered beans. The company even opposes labelling,
so consumers will not know that they are eating genetically engineered food. 
<p> 
Monsanto's hope is that Roundup Ready Soybeans will take over a substantial
portion of the huge soybean crop, including those grown in Argentina and
Brazil, in the next several years.    With the development of RRS, the chemical
industry and industrial agriculture are moving in a dangerous direction: they
are designing plants to adapt to chemical poisons. The use of Roundup Ready
Soybeans makes farmers dependent on a single corporation -- Monsanto -- thus
reducing their control over their land and seeds.    
<p> 
The genetically engineered soybean has brought the controversy surrounding the
use of genetic engineering in agriculture to a new level. The benefits of this
product accrues to Monsanto, which collects licensing fees from farmers and
assures itself more sales of Roundup, one of its most profitable  products.
However, Roundup Ready soybeans bring no benefit whatsoever to the consumer --
they are not cheaper, tastier or healthier. 
<p> 
Consumers are very suspicious of genetically engineered foods, and would prefer
not to buy them (<a href="roundup.html#app">see Appendix I</a>).    For soybean farmers, this reality should
be an urgent consideration.  Farmers can grow the GE-free soybeans that
consumers prefer and ensure that they are not mixed with the Roundup Ready
Soybean, or they run the risk of losing important soybean markets, and this may
hit soybean farmers in the pocketbook as well as the field.<p>
<hr>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td valign=top>
<img src="pix/rdup1.gif" width=127 height=52 ALT="THE INTERNATIONAL MARKET">
</td>
<td valign=top>
<font size=+1><b>Soybeans Are Everywhere</b><p></font>
The U.S. grows nearly half of the world's 135 million metric tonnes of soybeans
each year, and soybeans are the U.S.' second largest crop. Some form of soy is
found as much as 60 percent of processed consumer foods.   Rich in protein and natural
fat, most soybeans are processed into soy oil and soy meal. Most soy meal is
used to make high-protein animal feed; the remainder is used in food for human
consumption. The extracted oils, are supplied to food producers for further
processing. For numerous products, lecithin, which is obtained mainly from soy
oil, is added as a stabilizer and emulsifier.   
<p> 
Soy can be found in margarine, smoked herring, doughnuts, cakes, bread and
cookies, meat, baby food and diet foods, to name just a few. There are
literally tens of thousands of food products which contain soy in one form or
another.  Soy oil (and rape-seed oil) can be labelled "vegetable fats" or
"hydrogenated vegetable fat". Lecithin is sometimes labelled as E 322.  If
mixed with ordinary soybeans, consumers will have no idea whether RRS is
contaminating any of these products.
<p> 
<font size=+1><b>Bringing RRS to Market: No Consumer Right to Choose</b><p></font>   
Aware of the suspicion with which consumers view genetically engineered food,
Monsanto, together with the U.S. authorities, plans to mix RRS with ordinary
soybeans -- unlabelled -- thus contaminating the entire U.S. supply. So even if
products were labelled these actions would still make genetically engineered
food almost unavoidable and would rob consumers of the right to choose food
free of genetic manipulation, as well as robbing them of the right to know what
they are eating.   
<p> 
Now consumers are fighting back. A poll shows over 80 percent of consumers in
Germany, a major buyer of U.S. soybeans, are opposed to genetically engineered
food. Dozens of European companies, dealers and manufacturers have stated their
opposition to using genetically manipulated soy and are attempting to ensure
that they can obtain natural soybeans that have not bean mixed with the
RRS-soybean (<a href="roundup.html#app">see Appendix I</a>). In the U.S., some groups have called for a
boycott of certain brands containing soybean products.   
<p> 
In March, 1996 the Commission of the European Union (EU) gave the green light
for the export to Europe of Monsanto beans and their further processing in
Europe. The EU Commission even voted against the labelling of genetically
engineered products -- after the American government had threatened Europe with
trade sanctions. However the EU has delayed a decision on another genetically
Engineered crop, corn produced with genes patented by the Swiss company Ciba
Geigy.  This corn is being grown in the U.S.  Many  European countries have
objected to the distribution of this corn and there is a strong chance that it
will be rejected by the EU. The primary consern is that much of this corn is
used as animal feed and there is a high potential for anitbiotic resistance
developing in the animals and then being spread to humans.<p>
<hr>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td valign=top>
<img src="pix/rdup2.gif" width=127 height=55 ALT="THE RISKS OF GENETIC ENGINEERING">
</td>
<td valign=top>
<font size=+1><b>Genetic Pollution</b><p></font>
Genetic engineering allows genes to be transferred between completely unrelated
species. This means that new organisms with unpredictable metabolic processes
are created. Genetically engineered organisms have the ability to pass alien
genes (i.e. those transferred from a different species) onto following
generations and even to related wild species. The spread of these plants could
result in a long-term change in natural ecosystems.
<p> 
Although Roundup Ready soybeans have been studied for their agricultural
properties in a few field tests, there are still large gaps in our knowledge.
With the leap from limited experimental release in small fields to large-scale
growth the risk also increases. Will the new bean force out other plants? Will
it enter other ecosystems? Will it genetically contaminate wild relatives or
traditional strains? Will it change in the long term due to its resistance to
toxic substances? Nobody can answer these questions.   
<p> 
In the case of genetically engineered oilseed rape, scientists have shown how
easily oilseed rape crossbreeds with wild relatives and  therefore how easily
transfer of the herbicide resistance gene could  occur. Within the first
planting season it is estimated that a substantial part of wild weed population
could  acquire the gene for herbicide  tolerance. (Joergensen & Andersen, 1994,
Mikkelsen,et al., 1996).
<p> 
U.S. soybeans are also exported to Asia, Australia and the Pacific islands, the
home to the original wild soybean. In those regions, there is risk of
cross-breeding with wild soybean species.  In this way the foreign genes will
find their way into the wild populations of the bean.  The impacts on the
evolution of flora and natural ecosystems are unpredictable and irreversible.
<p> 
<font size=+1><b>Potential for Allergies</b><p></font>
Monsanto claims their tests on rats, cows, chickens and fish show no change in
the risk of allergy compared to the standard soybean. But the Monsanto
application to the Food and Drug Administration show that the feeding tests
were conducted for a maximum of ten weeks. This means that it is impossible to
forecast possible long-term effects and the effects on future generations.    
<p> 
After the introduction of RRS, people would act as unsuspecting guinea pigs as
even slight changes in protein structure can trigger off new allergies. For
example, when a soybean strain to which the genetic engineers had added a gene
from the Brazil nut was investigated at the University of Nebraska, it was
discovered that the ability to trigger off allergies had also been transferred
(Nordlee et al., 1996) . Monsanto offers that these are only suspected risks,
for which there is no proof. But in the case of the food industry, proof will
come too late to prevent harm. 
<p> 
When sheep cadavers were fed to cows, nobody thought that this could lead to
the mad cow disease (BSE epidemic), and once mad cow disease emerged, no-one
wanted to believe that it could be transferred to humans eating beef. The risks
of RRS are unknown, and indeed, unknowable. A precautionary approach should
apply.
<p> 
In 1989, a Japanese company introduced tryptophan on the American market.
Tryptophan was a food supplement produced from genetically-engineered bacteria.
But 37 people  died  and 1,500 more were left permanently disabled after taking
it, suffering  symptoms including inflammation of the joints, skin-swelling,
headaches, and suppression of the immune system (Jaffe, 1994).
<p>                              
Greenpeace believes that the tests Monsanto has carried out on RRS to be
inadequate (detailed paper available, Greenpeace International July 1996). 
<p> 
Monsanto have not possibly have conducted enough tests on this product to prove
that it is safe. By releasing it into the environment Monsanto is conducting a
worldwide experiment with humans and nature.<p>  
<hr>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td valign=top>
<img src="pix/rdup3.gif" width=127 height=54 ALT="MONSANTO AND ROUNDUP">
</td>
<td valign=top>
Monsanto is known in part as the company that developed and produced the
notorious defoliant Agent Orange used in the Vietnam War.  Monsanto was also
the inventor and world's main producer of polychlorinated biphenyls (PCBs), now
banned but still a menacing soil, water and food contaminant worldwide. 
<p> 
In recent years, Monsanto has made large investments to exploit genetic
engineering and describe themselves as leaders in the field of biotechnology.
Monsanto trys to market RRS as an environmentally beneficial product. In their
promotional materials the company calls their soy creation "an intelligent
solution in favour of the environment."  But in Monsanto's hands, the purpose
of genetic engineering seems to be not environmental protection or feeding the
hungry, but rather increased sales of their chemical herbicide Roundup.    
<p> 
Roundup is a chemical weed killer.  Some 15 percent of Monsanto's total sales
is accounted for by Roundup. In the U.S. alone up to 11,800 tonnes annually are
sprayed on fields, roadside verges and gardens. The patent for this 25-year-old
herbicide expires in the year 2000 and the price will undoubtedly drop as the
herbicide is more widely produced. It is obvious that Monsanto hopes Roundup
Ready Soybeans will secure profits after the herbicide patent has expired in
the year 2000.   
<p> 
There is significant evidence that Roundup can cause harm to the environment
and human health. Monsanto argues that the herbicide is rapidly degraded in the
soil and that even after long-term application there are no effects on the
environment.  This ignores the fact that every kind of herbicide leaves traces
in the environment - after all its aim is to destroy unwanted plants in the
fields. Monsanto says Roundup is as safe as aspirin or table salt.  But in
California, Roundup has been identified as the third most commonly reported
cause of pesticide-related illness amongst agricultural workers (Cox, 1995 b,
Pease et al., 1993). 
<p> 
Increased use of the herbicide Roundup may result in pollution of water and
lead to a further decreased wild plant diversity.  It could also harm animals
and beneficial soil micro-organisms. Glyphosate is claimed to be immobile in
soil as it readily binds to soil particles, however a new study indicates that
glyphosate can be readily released from soil particles, and therefore able to
leach into water (Piccolo et al., 1994). The active ingredient of Roundup has
already been detected in drinking water in Germany (Greenpeace, 1995). Roundup
can be very toxic to fish. In some situations concentrations as low as 10 parts
per million of glyphosate can kill fish (WHO, UNEP & ILO, 1994).
<p> 
Monsanto proudly states above all that Roundup is rapidly degraded by natural
micro-organisms into carbon monoxide, ammoniac and phosphate. They claim that
after a few weeks there are no detectable traces left. Yet glyphosate residues
have been found in strawberries (Cessna & Cain, 1992), lettuce, carrots, barley
(U.S. EPA, 1993), and fish (Wang et al., 994, Folmar et al., 1979). These
residues persisted long after the glyphosate was used. For example, lettuce,
carrots, and barley contained glyphosate residues at harvest when planted a
year after treatment (U.S. EPA, 1993).  Because RRS are tolerant to glyphosate
at twice the recommended levels of usage, farmers may be tempted to use extra
or be less careful in their application rates.
<p> 
<font size=+1><b>Chemical Dependency of the Roundup Ready Soybean</b><p></font>   
To create RRS, Monsanto has inserted parts of genes from a virus, a bacterium
and a petunia. With these genetic alterations the soybeans can tolerate the
poison Roundup.  Roundup blocks the metabolic processes of normal plants, thus
leading to the death of the plant. 
<p> 
When using RRS, farmers can and indeed must use Monsanto's Roundup during the
entire growing period, making their dependence on both the seed and the
pesticide even greater.  Monsanto claims that fewer herbicides will have to be
spread over the soy fields. Yet this is just theory. It is also possible that
farmers will need to increase the amounts of toxic substances used over time.   
<p> 
There is also a serious danger of the emergence of new herbicide tolerant weeds
through increased reliance on glyphosate which will necessitate the further use
of toxic chemicals.  There has already been a recent report of a glyphosate
resistance in ryegrass that has appeared in the natural environment in
Australia (New Scientist, 6 July 1996, p.6).  
<p> 
In fact, genetic engineers still know much too little about the interaction of
the genes with each other and the environment to be able to predict whether
their "building block constructions" actually work. Monsanto has already been
through some disasters in connection with resistance to pests and have not
always been able to keep their promises, for example with regard to cotton.    
<p>
<font size=+1><b>The Cotton Flop</b><p></font>   
Another Monsanto experiment in genetic engineering has turned into a gigantic
flop. Monsanto promised that their engineered cotton would form a poison
against caterpillar attack without using chemicals, i.e. with a
"self-protecting gene" against insect larvae. Furnished with the gene from the
bacterium Bacillus thuringiensis, the so-called Bollgard plants were supposed
to produce the Bt toxin in its own leaves. In the first year American cotton
farmers planted 700,000 hectares of this new strain. But Monsanto's
calculations went wrong: farmers found out that Bollgard did not produce enough
of the insecticide and not fast enough to protect the young shoots against the
caterpillars. The consequence was that in some fields up to 60 per cent of the
of the plants were successfully attacked by the caterpillars and at least 8,000
hectares in Texas were destroyed by the bollworm. The damage for this harvest
period is put at approximately 1 billion dollars (Nature Biotechnology Vol.14,
1996).  
<p> 
The negative  consequences for farmers and the environment will be much worse
if widespread planting of bollgard and other crops with the bt toxin gene cause
insect pests to become resistent to bt, as has been predicted by many
scientists.  Although the insect larvae are now exposed to the bt toxin, it
does not kill them, and this creates ideal conditions for them to become
resistant to this bacterial toxin.  Non-genetically engineered Bacillus
thuringiensis is a popular insecticide
particularly with organic farmers, but is used in ways much less likely to
create insect resistence. If widespread resistence to bt develops because of
its use in genetically engineered crops, organic foods may become more
expensive.<p>
<font size=+1><b>The Milk Hormone</b><p></font>   
Monsanto's best known genetically engineered product is probably recombinant
Bovine Growth Hormone (rBGH), injected into cows to increase milk production.
Like RRS, rBGH is of dubious benefit since U.S. farmers already produce a
surplus of milk. On the other hand it does harm cows' health and is difficult
to use and expensive for farmers.    
<p> 
Monsanto managed to obtain registration of this drug with the American Food and
Drug Administration (FDA) in spite of protests from consumer and farmers'
organizations. But rBGH has not been a commercial success in the U.S. and is
still prohibited in the European Union until at least the year 2,000.
Monsanto's position on labelling of milk containing rBGH is the same as that
for RRS: they are militantly opposed. Food companies which marked their
products as being rBGH-free, have been sued. One example of this was an action
brought against the Pure Milk and Ice Cream Company in Texas to force them to
withdraw their labels. The case was settled out of court, but Pure Milk and Ice
Cream still labels their products.   
<p>  
<font size=+1><b>The Roundup Ready Kitchen</b><p></font>   
In the U.S., Monsanto already has authorization to market several genetically
manipulated plants: apart from soybeans and Bollgard cotton, an
insect-resistant potato line called NewLeaf has also been registered. And it
does not stop there. The company has announced the marketing of other
genetically manipulated plants in coming years. 
<p>
<hr>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td valign=top>
<img src="pix/rdup4.gif" width=127 height=19 ALT="CONCLUSION">
</td>
<td valign=top> 
Greenpeace believes the spread of genetically engineered crops with their
potential for mutation, multiplication, and other unknown ecosystem effects are
one of the largest experiments with nature, our food supply, and our health
that humankind has ever embarked upon.   
<p> 
The future of agriculture and the world food supply lies in
environment-friendly, pesticide-free ecological farming. Roundup and the
Roundup Ready Soybean are a dead end.   With less than 2 percent of this year's
(1996) soybean crop Roundup Ready, there is still a chance prevent it from being used
in food products around the world. But time is running out. In Brazil, Monsanto
has submitted applications for growing the Roundup Ready soybean. In Argentina
permission to grow it has been granted. And in the United States the time for
harvesting and sorting the soybeans is at hand.   
<p> 
Greenpeace is calling on consumers to demand soybeans free of genetic
engineering and calling on farmers to refuse to plant the RRS-soybean in the
future. It is still possible for farmers to obtain markets for soybeans which
are sure to be free of RRS. It is equally possible for brokers and buyers to
find soybeans free of RRS.   Greenpeace is campaigning to ensure that the
entire U.S. supply of natural soybeans is not contaminated with Monsanto's
Roundup Ready Soybean.
<p> 
<font size=+1><b>GREENPEACE POLICY STATEMENT:</b><p></font>
In the light of the known risks of introducing  genetically engineered
organisms into the environment, Greenpeace is opposed to the growing,
production and marketing of genetically engineered crops and food. 
<p> 
<font size=+1><b>GREENPEACE RECOMMENDATIONS:</b></p></font>
Greenpeace recommends:
<ul>    
<li>that consumers, food retailers, soybean brokers and processors demand
soy products free from of genetically engineered  manipulations.</li> 
<li>that farmers avoid the Roundup Ready Soybean and plant only
non-gentically engineered soybeans and other crops.</li>
</ul>
<p>
<hr>
<b>Also see the related report <a href="critique.html">"Not Ready for Roundup: A Critique 
of Monsanto's Risk Evaluation"</a>.</b>
<hr>
</td>
</tr>
