<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0><tr><th><font size=+2><b>
Quicktime Movie 
</th></tr><tr><td align=center><table border=10 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 WIDTH=160 
HEIGHT=144><tr><td><EMBED
SRC="../movies/history.mov"
WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=144 autoplay=true></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td align=left>
<b>In the clip:</b>
<br>
For most people, North Sea fishing is linked to images of fishermen fighting the elements to catch cod, herring or plaice. But during the last 40 years a
huge "industrial" fishery has grown up largely unnoticed by the public, despite its massive size. It catches fish not for the table, but to be ground up into
industrial products such as fish meal and oil. 

Many consumers will be surprised to know that they are eating industrial fishery products either indirectly (used as food for livestock, poultry and
farmed fish) or directly but anonymously, as "animal fat" in cakes, biscuits and margarine. <BR><HR>
