<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>AREAS SENSITIVE TO INDUSTRIAL FISHING</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="9CFCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">

<table border=0 width=100% cellpadding=5>
<tr><td>

<table border=2 width=100% cellpadding=5><tr><td>
<a href="nsea.html"><img align=right WIDTH=60 HEIGHT= 80 src="../icons/nsea11.gif"></a>
<BR><BR><H2>AREAS SENSITIVE TO INDUSTRIAL FISHING</H2>
</td></tr></table>

</td>
</tr>
</table>

<P><img align=right border=0 width=243 height=398 src="../pics/areas.gif">
 
GREENPEACE is calling for urgent regulation of industrial 
fisheries in the North Sea.
Catch limits should be set for these fisheries based on the 
precautionary approach,
by-catch of non-target species should be eliminated and 
industrial fisheries should not be allowed in sensitive areas.
 
<P>GREENPEACE therefore calls on North Sea Governments to formally 
identify sensitive areas in the North Sea in which no industrial 
fishing should take place as
a matter of urgency.
 
<P>WHAT ARE SENSITIVE AREAS?
 
<P>Those areas in the North Sea where there are reasonable grounds 
for suspecting that industrial fishing may have a 
disproportional impact, either upon the target
species, or upon other parts of the marine ecosystem.
 
<P>All areas can be identified temporally and/or spatially. This 
identification may be
permanent, seasonal or temporary.
 
<BR>Some major features of sensitive/critical areas include:-
  
<BR>a. nursery areas, spawning areas, or areas with high abundance 
of juveniles, of non target species and/or
 
<BR>b. areas where there may be a significant bycatch of other 
species and/or  
<BR>c. areas where there may be significant risk of damaging 
competition with natural
predators eg. other fish, birds or marine mammals and/or
 
<BR>d. areas where the target species is particularly vulnerable 
(eg. discreet local populations and/or relatively rare species)

 
<P>GREENPEACE, considers it likely that the following areas will 
fulfill these criteria
when North Sea Governments complete identification of such areas 
and therefore recommends that in the interim industrial 
fisheries be excluded from these areas immediately.These areas 
may overlap. This list is not intended to be comprehensive.
  
<P>1. The Plaice Box
 
<BR>57o00' N - 07o15' E, 55o00' N - 07o15' E, 55o00' N - 07o00' E, 
<BR>54o30' N - 07o00' E, 54o30' N - 07o30' E, 54o00' N - 07o30' E, 
<BR>54o00' N - 07o00' E, 53o50' N - 06o00' E, 53o50' N - 05o00' E, 
<BR>53o30' N - 05o00' E, 53o30' N - 04o15' E, 53o00' N - 04o15' E.  
<P>Is an extension of the 12 mile zone North of the Netherlands, in 
the German Bight
and along the coast of Jutland.
 
<P>It has been subject to fishing restrictions because it is a 
nursery area for plaice and
cod (Daan et al. 1990) Currently, fishing vessels over 300 Hp 
are not allowed within the box.
 
<P>'In the fisheries policy special attention is given to the 12 
mile zone. This is
because the areas has a special function as a nursery area. It 
is in the interest of
the fishing industry to protect nursery areas. EU policy support 
this objective. An
example could be to increase protection within the plaice box.' 
Vissen naar Evenwicht, Regeringsbeslissing, Structuurnota Zee-en 
Kustvisserij, Min. van LNV, January 1993 (Veenman Drukkers, 
Wageningen)
 
<P>The area is also important for breeding Sandwich tern 
populations and  for  red and
black-throated divers, red-necked grebe, common scoter,  little 
gull and common gull. Skkov, H, Durinck J,Leopold MF and  Tasker 
ML 1995. Important Bird Areas for Seabirds in the North  Sea. 
Birdlife International, Cambridge.  
 
 
<P>2. The Norway Pout box
 
<P>Defined in EC Regulation No 3094/86 as 'that part of the North 
Sea which is under
the sovereignty or jurisdiction of a Member State and bounded to 
the South by a line running eastward from a point on the east 
coast of Scotland at 56 degrees north to 2 degrees east, thence 
northwards to 58 degrees north, thence westward to 0 degrees 
30'west, thence north to 59 degrees 15'north, thence east to 1 
degree east, thence north to 60 degrees north, thence west to 
longitude 0 degree,
thence northward to 60 degrees 30' north, thence westward to the 
east coast of the Shetland Islands, thence westward from the 
west coast of the Shetland Islands
at 60 degrees north to 3 degrees west, thence southwards to 58 
degrees 30'north and thence westward to the Scottish coast.'
 
<P>'The aim of the Norway Pout Box...is to protect juvenile stocks 
of haddock and whiting form industrial fishing for Norway Pout. 
Massive exploitation of the latter
with small mesh nets inevitably produces a by-catch of young 
whitefish.' Towards a Revised CFP, M. Wise 1984 Methuen and co.
 
<P>Currently, industrial fishing for Norway Pout is not allowed in 
the area.  
 
 
 
<P>3. The Western Margin
 
<P>This area occupies the north-western margin of the North Sea, as 
defined by successive Ministerial Conferences on the Protection 
of the North Sea. It extends
from Cape Wrath north to 62 degrees north, east to the 0 degree 
line, south to 54 degrees 45' north,
where it intercepts the English coast close to the Withern Sea 

<P>This area is of international importance for seabirds. The vast 
majority of this zone
encompasses the second and third most important areas for 
seabirds  in the North Sea. Many fish eating seabirds have 
important concentrations here.  
Skkov, H, Durinck J, Leopold MF and Tasker ML 1995. Important 
Bird Areas for Seabirds in the North Sea. Birdlife 
International, Cambridge.  
<P>4. A UK northeast coastal zone extending seaward for 30 miles in 
order to encompass coastal fish nursery areas. The zone extends 
from Cape Wrath in a direction east and south to Flamborough 
head and also encircles the Orkney and Shetland Isles.
 
<P>Coastal areas are particularly important as nursery areas for 
many juvenile fish species. Both saithe and herring have nursery 
grounds on the Scottish northern and eastern coasts.
 
<P>In addition, the 'region off the North and North-West coasts of 
Scotland is an important spawning area for both cod and haddock'
 
<P>'It is probable that a large proportion of the cod in the 
Northern North Sea spend
their first one or two years of life close inshore along the UK 
coast where they cannot be caught by conventional survey gear'. 
 
<P>Daan, NPJ Bromley, JRG Hislop and NA Nielsen (1990), Ecology of 
North Sea Fish, Netherlands Journal of Sea Research 26, 343-386. 
 
<P>In addition, sandeel population dynamics are poorly understood 
and the stocks in Scottish coastal waters may be distinct from 
those in other parts of the North Sea.
 
<P>'Away from traditional areas, the grounds close to the Scottish 
coast have become
increasingly important [for fisheries] in recent years. Further 
studies are necessary
to show whether sandeels on these grounds may be part of a 
separate stock from fish in the Northern and Southern areas. 
[ie.of the North Sea in general]. It is certainly clear that the 
division of these grounds between the present areas is 
inappropriate. It is possible that similar comments also apply 
to the areas close to
the Danish coast.'
 
<P>Report of the Working Group on the assessment of Norway pout and 
Sandeel. ICES Council Meeting 1995: Assessment 5.


<P>5. The Wee Bankie Area (including the Wee Bankie/Scalp Bank/Marr 
Bank/Cockenzie Bank)
 
<P>The Wee Bankie area is defined approximately as the area bounded 
by a line east from Gin Head at 56 degrees north, 2 degrees 
35'west, to 25'west and then North to 40'north and then east to 
Boddin Point at 56 degrees 40' north, 2 degrees 30' west.
 
<P>The area is particularly important for seabird populations. 
Major seabird colonies
in the vicinty include the Isle of May, Bass Rock and St Abb's 
Head.(Lloyd, C., ML
Tasker & K Partridge (1991) The Status of Seabirds in  Britain 
and Ireland. T & AD
Poyser, London.
 
<P>6. Flamborough Head
 
<P>4 degrees 7' north, 0 degree longitude
 
<P>Flamborough Head is an area of special scientific interest, an 
SSSI, and has been
recommended by English Nature as a sensitive marine area. The 
area supports one of England's most important seabird colonies.
 

<BR><HR><BR>



 
</body></html>


 

 





