                           <head>          <H4>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE

        MV GREENPEACE TO JOIN MORUROA NUCLEAR TEST PROTEST 
                   AS PRESSURE ON FRANCE GROWS
  </H4></head><body>
<P>LONDON, Thursday July 20 -- The MV Greenpeace will sail next Monday
(July 24) from Barcelona to join the Rainbow Warrior, Vega and an
international peace flotilla at the Moruroa nuclear test site in the
South Pacific, Greenpeace announced today.
 
<P>In an escalation of pressure on France's President Chirac to reverse
his decision to resume nuclear testing in September, the MV
Greenpeace will join other vessels at Moruroa in late August.

<P>Greenpeace's Xavier Pastor, on board the MV Greenpeace, said the
ship's 20,000 kilometre voyage symbolised the opposition of millions
of Europeans uniting with protestors in the Pacific region against
nuclear testing.
 
<P>"We challenge European governments to listen to the anger of their
people and to oppose France's resumption of testing with the same
determination, urgency and commitment as Greenpeace," Pastor said.
"International condemnation of France's decision must increase over
the next few weeks if President Chirac is to see sense and abandon
the testing programme."
 <P>Speaking from the SV Rainbow Warrior en route to Fiji, Greenpeace's
Stephanie Mills said Greenpeace's presence at Moruroa -- currently
the yacht Vega, the Danish vessel Bifrost, and an inflatable hidden
in the vicinity of the test site -- would be dramatically increased
by the end of August.
 
<P>"We appeal again to the international community to join us in yachts
and boats outside the test site, to show President Chirac the
strength of opposition to nuclear testing," she said.  "The crew of
the Rainbow Warrior are committed to return to Moruroa, not alone but
with an international flotilla of protest."
 
<P>The MV Greenpeace will travel via the Panama Canal and its transit
to Moruroa is expected to take 40-50 days.  The ship will provide
support to the Rainbow Warrior and a fleet of vessels sailing from
New Zealand, Australia and other parts of the world.<br>
                                 ENDS
<P>Contact: 
Blair Palese, Greenpeace Communications, +44 171 833 0600
Stephanie Mills on board the SV Rainbow Warrior +872 1300312


<P>Crew list to follow:

