<head>

<br><br><h4>GREENPEACE INFLATABLES NOW IN MORUROA LAGOON IN NUCLEAR TEST PROTEST</h4>

<br>Moruroa--4 September 1995--Two inflatables carrying Greenpeace activists have
just entered Moruroa lagoon to protest the imminent resumption of French nuclear
testing. 

<br><br>The two boats were launched from a vessel in the peace flotilla and entered
Moruroa lagoon at 5.21 am local time.  They were in radio contact with the
flotilla, and heading for the house of the French Naval commander in charge at
Moruroa - Admiral Philippe Euverte, where they hope to deliver their protest
against the imminent test. 

<br><br>It is not clear where and when that test will be carried out -Moruroa Atoll or
nearby Fangataufa.  

<br><br>"This protest is a last-hour attempt to stave off the test, due to be detonated
at any minute. It comes from Greenpeace, on behalf of the more than 5 million
people who signed our petition opposing testing," said Thomas Schultz,
Greenpeace International nuclear campaigner in Papeete, Tahiti. 

<br><br>"The French military have seized two of our vessels, smashed their
communications, used unreasonable force against our people, but we refuse to be
silenced," said Schultz.

<br><br>The entry by the inflatable crews into the Moruroa test site is part of what is
expected to be an on-going protest by the international peace flotilla.  About
25 boats are at or drawing near to the 12-mile exclusion zone. Another vessel
left Tahiti today carrying politicians from Japan, Australia, Sweden, Italy and
Luxembourg. 
                            

<br><br>For information:  Greenpeace in Papeete:  ++689 770 613;  
++689 770 614
<br>Greenpeace Communications: ++44 171 833 0600</body></html>


