<head><title>Chirac's speech - Greenpeace's response</title></head><body>
<h4>FRENCH PRESIDENT CHIRAC'S TELEVISED SPEECH WILL INCREASE 
            OPPOSITION TO NUCLEAR TESTS: GREENPEACE</h4>

<P>PARIS, 5 September 1995 -- The refusal of France's President
Chirac, on France 2 (1300h programme), to announce the date of
the first of a series of nuclear tests is an insult to the French
people and to international public opinion who are overwhelmingly
against the resumption of testing.

<P>"Following Commander Cousteau's appeal yesterday for France not
to resume testing, Greenpeace has a glimmer of hope," said Remi
Parmentier, President of Greenpeace France. "Chirac claims he has
listened to the opinions of experts in France but with Jacques
Cousteau, who lead a mission of experts to Moruroa in 1987,
stepping down from a Presidential commission over the testing
issue, it is clear that he does not have the support of his own
experts."

<P>President Chirac continues to turn a deaf ear to world opposition
to testing and seems unconcerned with that as well as that of the
63 percent of his own French people who are also opposed.  He has
also ignored the violence used by French commandos against
Greenpeace activists onboard the two Greenpeace boats, from whom
we still have no news."

<P>"Far from curbing public opinion, the French government's action
will exacerbate the opposition to the nuclear tests planned by
President Chirac," Parmentier said.

<P>Contact: 
Remi Parmentier, Penelope Komites, Greenpeace France: +33 1 47
70 46 89 </body></html>


