<head><title>                                    
 
GREENPEACE ACTIVISTS ATTEMPT TO OCCUPY DRILLING RIG AT FRENCH
TEST SITE IN FANGATAUFA ATOLL:-19 September</title></head><body><p> SEPTEMBER 19, 1995  

<H4>GREENPEACE ACTIVISTS ATTEMPT TO OCCUPY DRILLING RIG AT FRENCH
TEST SITE IN FANGATAUFA ATOLL, MOST PROBABLE SITE FOR SECOND TEST 
 </H4>
<p>ABOARD SV MANUTEA, Off 12-mile Exclusion Zone, Sept. 19 -- In a
daring new wave of protests against French nuclear testing,
Greenpeace activists, in a coordinated maneuver from the 20-boat
Peace Flotilla, have entered the French exclusion zone around
Fangataufa atoll, the most likely test site for France's second
and more powerful nuclear blast. 
 
<p>The two activists, Belgian Roger Gregoor and New Zealander
Rachael Sanson, planned to drive their inflatable to a testing
drill rig located in Fangataufa lagoon and occupy it as long as
possible. Fangataufa has traditionally been used for extremely
high-yield nuclear testing, and the upcoming test expected to be
detonated there could be up to 150 kilotons.  
 
<p>France's larger nuclear tests were moved from Moruroa to
Fangataufa in 1988.  At the time the French military conceded
that this was because of the extent of damage already caused at
Moruroa, effectively admitting that Moruroa could no longer
sustain larger tests in the 100 kiloton range.  Since 1966,
France has tested five atmospheric and 8 underground tests at
Fangataufa, the last test in 1991 being 130 kilotons.

<p>As European Union members plan for an environmental review to
examine the impact of French testing, the Greenpeace activists
challenged the EU to come to Fangataufa, the most contaminated
of the French testing sites. Said Gregoor, "Let them come and
study the damage done to this former Pacific paradise.  However,
we advise them to use extreme caution.  We are going to the
drilling rig, not the atoll--even the French won't let their
workers stay for long periods here because of the contamination."
 
<p>Despite constant harassment from French warships, jets and
helicopters, the determined members of the Peace Flotilla have
carried out continuous incursions into Moruroa and now,
Fangataufa, with borrowed boats, battered outboards and wooden
canoes.  Today the ship Machias is leaving from Tahiti with a
cargo full of fresh supplies for the Peace Flotilla.
 
<p>As France has never allowed an independent long-term scientific
study of Fangataufa, the EU environmental commission may be the
first allowed, although only for a two or three week "study."  

<p>"Inviting scientists in for a week or two to 'conduct research'
is not only ridiculous, it is pathetic," said Audrey Cardwell,
nuclear campaigner aboard the Greenpeace Manutea.  "France has
damaged the people and environment of the South Pacific for
decades with its blind determination to test nuclear weapons
here.  If France won't listen to the people of the Pacific who
rightly own this land, then maybe pressure from its neighbors in
Europe will make a difference."
 
<p>CONTACT: Audrey Cardwell/Sanae Shida On Manutea +872.63.676.9710 
<br>         Thomas Schultz, GP Tahiti, +789.433.280
<br>         Tom Clements/Jonathan Hall, GP US, +202.319.2506/2542 -</body></html>


