<head><title>SEPTEMBER 21, 1995
 
YOUNG NEW ZEALANDERS ENTER FRENCH EXCLUSION ZONE ON SURF SKI</title></head><body>
<P>
 
<H4>YOUNG NEW ZEALANDERS ENTER FRENCH EXCLUSION ZONE ON SURF SKI</H4>
 
<P>MORUROA, September 21 -- In a continuing wave of direct actions
against French nuclear testing, today two young New Zealand
activists from the 20-boat Peace Flotilla paddled into the
12-mile exclusion zone surrounding Moruroa atoll on a surf ski
named the Aotearoa Arc.
 
<P>The two activists, Daniel Godoy, 22, of Wellington, and Daniel
Salmon, 25, of Auckland entered the nuclear test exclusion zone
early this morning as an act of opposition by New Zealand youth
to French nuclear testing in the South Pacific.
 
<P>"The Pacific Island and Rim countries are united in their
repugnance at the nuclear detonation at Moruroa on September 5. 
Any future tests should be canceled immediately because these
atolls are riddled with cracks," said Daniel Salmon. "We hope our
protest will provide impetus for continued worldwide youth
opposition to the French nuclear testing program."
 
<P>The Peace Flotilla has been the subject of continuous harassment
by French warships, fighter-planes and helicopters.  "All less
direct attempts by the Peace Flotilla to discuss French actions
and intimidation with the French Navy have been ignored," added
Salmon. "So we are entering the Zone wanting answers."
 
<P>Earlier in the day, two Greenpeace activists were released from
French custody after entering the exclusion zone around the
neighboring atoll of Fangataufa.  The activists reported that
preparations were being made for another more powerful test at
Fangataufa, furthering speculation that the site will be used for
the second blast, possibly one reaching the 150 kiloton
threshold. 
 
<P>A delegation of scientists from the European Commission,
currently in Tahiti, have been refused to carry out any
independent sampling of the two test sites.  
"The delegation from the EC must be allowed to conduct a
thoroughly independent investigation of nuclear testing on
Moruroa and Fangataufa," said Salmon.  "The EC has a duty to
ensure their member state France shows international
responsibility by ending its escalation of the nuclear arms
race."
  
<P>Daniel Godoy, who sold his car to secure a passage with the Peace
Flotilla, left with encouraging words: "We are entering French
territory with the support and good wishes of all the New
Zealanders who sacrificed so much to make the 6000 mile
round-trip voyage to protest at Moruroa."
 
<P>CONTACT: NZ PEACE FLOTILLA, +649-3789163
<br>        AUDREY CARDWELL, GREENPEACE MANUTEA, +872.636.76.9710</body></html>



