<P><br><br><br><br><br><H4>PEACE FLOTILLA PRESS RELEASE</H4>

Peace Flotilla Protests in Papeete<p>

Papeete:  The Moruroa Peace Flotilla took their anti-nuclear protest to
the heart of Papeete this morning, sailing in formation around the
harbour and past a French warship, La Nivose, berthed at the military
docks.<p>

Flying banners that said  Stop Bombing Moruroa ,  Le Jour de Honte est
Arrivi  (The Day of Shame has Arrived) and  Vive le Pacifique , the four
yachts: Joie, Sudden Laughter, Te Kaitoa and Carumba, began their
protest at 8am local time.  A fifth flotilla yacht, Guinevere, is also
in Papeete but was unable to participate because she is undergoing
repairs.  Also on board the protesting yachts were local Tahitian people
and a group of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islanders.

Two inflatable boats carrying about six military personnel each, a
police launch and a harbour patrol vessel followed the protest closely.
The harbour patrol approached each yacht as they were finishing the
protest to issue them with a  ticket  for movements in the harbour
without permission (this carries a small fine).<p>

      We are determined to continue our protests against the crime
of nuclear testing in the Pacific, and while we cannot physically stay
out at Moruroa for ever, we are here to show solidarity with anti-
nuclear efforts in Papeete,  said the
skipper of Sudden Laughter, Nigel Joy.   We will also    [text missing]   
<P> New Zealand Maid (NZ)
        <BR>Pozzualana (US)
        <BR>Photina (NZ)
        <BR>Pickety Witch (NZ)
        <BR>Rainbow Warrior (Netherlands)
        <BR>R. Tucker Thompson (NZ)
        <BR>Sudden Laughter (NZ)
        <BR>Suliven (sp?) (en route from Scotland to New
Zealand) <BR>Tara (Germany)
        <BR>Tau (Fiji)
        <BR>Te-Au-O-Tonga (Cook Islands)
        <BR>Triptych (NZ)
        <BR>Te Kaitoa (NZ)
        <BR>Tui (NZ government)
        <BR>Vega (Canada)

<P>Altogether, by the time these ships return home, they
will have sailed enough miles to encircle the globe eight
times.<p>
