<title>Greenpeace Moruroa Press Release</title>
</head>
<body><body bgcolor="#ffffff"<font size="+1">

<P align=right> <a href="rw.html"><image align=right src="srwa.gif" border=0 ></a>
<a href="oct28b.html"><image align=right src="irig.gif" border=0 ></a>
<a href="pr.html#october"><image align=right src="iup.gif" border=0 >
<a href="oct25.html"><image align=right src="ilef.gif" border=0 ></a>
<P><br><br><br><br><br><H4>THIRD FRENCH NUCLEAR TEST 
   FLIES IN THE FACE OF CONTINUED INTERNATIONAL CONDEMNATION   </H4> 

                  
                            
       <p> Greenpeace Vessel Caramba Remains Off Test Site
 
<p>PAPEETE, 28 OCTOBER, 1995 -- (GP) Greenpeace condemned France's
third nuclear test, an estimated 60 kiloton explosion off Moruroa
Atoll at noon local time, saying that the latest test ignores
massive and ever-growing international opposition. 
 
<p>Greenpeace's vessel Caramba and one other peace flotilla vessel
remain just outside the test area bearing witness to the ongoing
French testing program.
 
<p>"Despite hundreds of nations coming together to celebrate 50
years of the United Nations, the absence of political will to
collectively take action to stop one rogue nation from further
nuclear tests has never been more obvious," said Greenpeace's
John Mate on board the Caramba.  "France should urgently heed the
wishes of a majority of nations and stop all nuclear tests
immediately."
 
<p>French President Chirac will visit the United Kingdom on Sunday
to discuss ongoing nuclear cooperation between the two countries
as well as the United States.  John Major will also travel to New
Zealand in mid-November to meet with Commonwealth states where
he is expected to face a storm of criticism for his complicity
in the French testing program.
 
<p>This month, the 113 countries that make up the non-aligned
movement recently called for an immediate cessation of all
nuclear testing and for a moratorium to be put in place until a
Comprehensive Test Ban (CTBT) can be agreed.  The European
Parliament this week passed a resolution condemning any further
nuclear testing by either France or China stating the risk future
tests could pose to the Non-Proliferation Treaty as well as the
global environment. 
 
<p>"Although there are now only two vessels left at the site of this
environmental crime, Greenpeace is here representing the millions
of individuals and the 159 countries opposed to France's nuclear
testing," Mate said.  "We call on those peoples and nations not
to give up hope -- collective will, political and diplomatic
pressure can bring an end to this nuclear threat."
 
 
 
                            
<p>Contact:
John Mate, on board the Caramba: +872-6244-5510
<br>Glynn Walters, Greenpeace in Tahiti: +689-433-282.
</body></html>

