<title>More Information: Reactors</title></head>

<body !--background="../icons/nukbac5b.gif"-- bgcolor="#FF595B" text=#000000 link="#008000" alink= "#000099" vlink="#139000">
<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0 WIDTH=600>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN=TOP>

<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=7><TR><TD WIDTH=560 ALIGN=LEFT>
<FONT SIZE=+2 FACE="MS SERIF">T H E &nbsp F A I L U R E &nbsp O F&nbsp
 N U C L E A R <br> P O W E R</FONT>
</TD>

<TD WIDTH=40>
<A HREF="reactmi.html" onMouseOver="moveover('Back to Reactors Main Page'); return true"><img valign=middle width=42 height=60 border=0 src="../icons/nreacth.gif" alt="Reactors"></a>
</TD>


</TR></TABLE>
<HR width=600 align=left>
<!--TEXT TABLE----------------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=580><TR><TD>
<FONT FACE="MS SERIF">

<p>The nuclear industry in North America and Western Europe is not yet dead but it is 
desperate.  The decline of orders at home has forced it to look elsewhere for a new 
market -- that market is Central & Eastern Europe (CEE) and Asia.   The nuclear 
industry is poised and ready to strike again. 

<p>In CEE and the former Soviet Union, there are still reactors under construction in 
Czech Republic, Russia, Slovakia, Romania and Ukraine.    With few orders in their 
own countries, many Western firms, notably, Siemens (Germany), Electricite de 
France and Westinghouse (United States) are hoping to form key partnerships with 
Eastern firms for the completion of these reactors.   In addition Siemens is proposing 
to  become involved in the next generation of reactors in Russia, with the 
development of the VVER 640 reactors.     Other Western firms are interested in 
building new their new generation of reactors, with Westinghouse discussing 
construction of the AP 600 in both Hungary and Lithuania.
 
<p>Many nuclear power plants in CEE are in crisis.    Western experts have classified 27 
operating reactors in CEE as 'high risk', that is, reactors that are very likely to have a 
serious accident in the next years.    Greenpeace believes that these reactors should 
be closed immediately.  These reactors could be shutdown by utilising the huge 
potential for energy efficiency and the introduction of renewable energy sources.
 
<p> In Asia - Japan, South Korea, China, Taiwan and India have plans to expand their 
nuclear power supplies.  While Indonesia is also soon to embark on a nuclear power 
programme in a region known for its high earthquake frequency.  

<p>By forcing itself on newly industrialising countries the nuclear industries of Western 
Europe and North America hope to survive.  However, if these nations do continue to 
invest in nuclear power, they will find themselves increasingly handicapped in the 
world community, having to deal with environmental and economic problems that are 
intrinsic to nuclear power.
 
<a name="chernobyl">
<p><FONT SIZE=+1 FACE="MS SERIF">A C C I D E N T S &nbsp D O  &nbsp H A P P E N
 </font>
<p>In April 1986, staff undertaking tests on safety systems at <a href="../nukes/chernob/index.html">Chernobyl</a> nuclear power 
station in the former Soviet Union, switched off the emergency cooling system and 
other essential safety systems.  The reactor became unstable and reached 100 
times normal power.  It then took just 4 seconds for the nuclear reactor to explode, 
leading to the world's worst ever civil nuclear accident.
 
<p>The western world has also already had a taste of the potential disasters that could 
be caused by their reactors.    In 1979 the United States' experienced a major 
accident at the Three Mile Island nuclear reactor. Human error amplified a technical 
fault that occurred and caused the reactor to meltdown (meltdown happens when the 
core of a reactor gets so hot that the fuel rods actually melt).  Radioactive gases 
poured into the atmosphere.  It took days for emergency evacuation plans to be put 
into operation. Local people accused the government of a big cover-up. Independent 
experts have shown that cancer deaths and infant mortality in the area are several 
times the national average.
 
<p>The threat posed to the world community by both eastern and western nuclear 
reactors is enormous. These accidents have shown nuclear energy to be one of the 
most highly dangerous and potentially lethal human creations.


 <p><FONT SIZE=+1 FACE="MS SERIF">A  &nbspC O S T L Y  &nbspM I S T A K E</font>
 
<p>Nuclear power is highly uneconomic. Where market forces have been permitted to 
follow their course, nuclear power has proved uncompetitive.  Moreover, the full 
economic costs arising from the decommissioning of old plants, the long-term 
management of radioactive wastes and the inevitable periodic accidents, have yet to 
be incorporated into the total costs of nuclear power.

<p>After a Review on the privatisation of the British nuclear power industry, the 
government deemed that there was no economic justification for public funding of 
any new reactors.  In December 1995,  British Energy announced the cancellation of 
two proposed nuclear power stations.
<center>

<BR><BR><HR width=400><BR>
 

<br><br>
 </FONT>
</td></tr></table>
</td></tr></table>
